15	Putting the Nordic Model on the Map: A Digital Approach to Global Conceptual Circulation	The five Nordic countries are sometimes described as a ‘Nordic model’, with reference to similarities in the social and political institutions, structures and cultures of the five Nordic countries, and the policies which have shaped these. There are, however, some profound disagreements over what these similarities are, and the extent to which they are available or relevant for transfer to other national contexts. The Nordic model is a highly flexible concept, the meanings of which have evolved over time and defy straightforward definitions.  \n\nResearch on the Nordic model and on related concepts – most importantly the Swedish, Danish, Norwegian, Finnish, and Icelandic models – has established how the term has been shaped by political and scholarly debates, and how evolving meanings of the term have been inextricably linked with interactions between Nordic and foreign actors. Despite recent advances, including efforts to apply digital tools like Google Ngram to visualize conceptual usage over time, there are still many gaps in our knowledge about the origins and spread of the Nordic model and its circulation in an international context. \n\nThis article uses digital methods to provide a systematic overview of the circulation of the Nordic model concept in academic publications. Using metadata from over 5000 publication records between 1980 and 2018, gathered from nine academic databases, this article provides both a starting point for and an example of using digital methods to explore a global conceptual history of the Nordic model. This approach contributes to the growing field of digital conceptual history, which is still coming to grips with methodological concerns over transnational and global perspectives.\n\nNarration – transmedia story telling. A digital approach allows us to pursue a spatial analysis of the circulation of the concept along geographic and temporal dimensions. By using Leaflet for R to plot publication data according to authors’ affiliation, we will build, analyze, and share an interactive map of the appearances of the ‘Nordic model’ in metadata. As far as we are aware, this is the first time that the historical development of the concept will be visually explored. The map will not only allow us to highlight moments and locations where conceptual circulation intensified, but also contrast the Nordic model with its related concepts in two different language areas: English and French. Wedding this visual investigation to discussions about the global application of the Nordic model allows for new perspectives on the concept’s transfer and transformation, including illuminating the complex exchanges between Nordic and international scholars. The result is an opportunity to document and verify narratives of the rise and development of the concept in both the Global North and Global South, spot new trends and critical junctures, and more systematically illustrate when, how, and by whom the Nordic region was ‘modellized.’\nThe goals laid out above advance our contribution to digital hermeneutics, as we reflect on the merits of digital methods for tracking conceptual circulation. Focusing on academic records offers for instance a perspective on the intertextuality of a concept, while at the same mitigating a sense of its transdiscursive properties. This latter issue opens for a discussion of an alternative, aborted method for studying the Nordic model concept: writing a global history from the archived internet. According to Niels Brügger, with the Internet being, ‘transnational by nature, and since global issues and events transcend the national Web sphere, it would be obvious to undertake transnational and comparative research projects.’ However, the attempts to study the Nordic model’s global development using the archived internet in fact demonstrated the methodological limitations of working with national digital archives.\n\nData layer. By providing the interactive map for readers’ use, while also making the datasets and codes on which they are based public, we aim to both produce a study that is transparent and reproducible and to inspire continued research into the Nordic model’s conceptual development using digital tools.\n	2020-12-16 10:55:04.68238+00	2020-12-29 11:12:51.732037+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5745-0534	Aarhus University	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Rom-Jensen	Byron	ACCEPTED	t	\N	PojAuvdCpvPr	\N
18	#Cancelculture: How the modern ostracism faces free speech.	This article aims to analyse how the social-web phenomena of "cancel culture" represents some historical aspects put in focus, mostly regarding how social minorities have acquired major voices through the internet and its vast approach to democracy. Hence, the term "cancel culture" does have plenty of meanings, but most of them can be converged into the understanding of how certain groups and urban tribes have decided to deal with archaic world views.\nWith so, this article focuses on the historical relationship built among liberal and progressive web users - mostly millennials and gen z people, but not limited to - and the ones who are into the "canceled" spectrum - mostly the ones who carry on historically oppressive issues and spread those ideas. Therefore, this project coligates how freedom of speech is managed through such groups, once, while the last one identifies their speeches as valid due democracy and the guarantee of verbal expression, the first one "cancels" these people due non-accordance ideas in favor of progressive calls, democracy and inclusion. \nThus, through a historical presentation of how democracy and verbal expression have shaped themselves during the last decade inside the web and its sociology, this article aims to understand and expose how this new way of social-fighting - a modern ostracism - faces, both in favor and against, free speech.	2020-12-25 21:55:41.933214+00	2020-12-29 13:59:45.252641+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0003-4654-1340	São Paulo State University	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	da Silva Lino	Pedro Henrique	DECLINED	t	\N	TfPaqit7u93D	\N
21	Wiki and theory: writing and making sense of Wikipedia’s digital historical accounts 	How can we make sense of Wikipedia’s historical articles? Are they reliable? Can we make them reliable? Are Wikipedia’s entries on history a feasible source to understand the post digital experience of time? What is the meaning of Wikipedia’s digital historiography? \nSince the seminal works of Roy Rosenzweig (2006), Wikipedia is recognized as containing one of the largest works of online historical writing. More recently, scholars began to regard it as a primary source as well (Wyatt 2020). At least from 2010, professors are editing on the platform through Wikimedia Education Program. \nThis article aims to present the project Theory of History on Wikipedia, based at Universidade Federal de Santa Catarina, Brazil, as well as to highlight the impact of this professional editing on the platform. \nDuring its first phase (2018-2020), THW’s main goal was to create and develop Portuguese speaking Wikipedia “featured articles” (FA) on theory of history and history of historiography. Additionally, to uphold FA’s requirements the project has created or developed more than 100 secondary entries. In its second phase, THW proponents are analysing and publishing data concerning the nature of historical writing on Wikipedia.  \nProposed in three layers, this article is an exploratory survey about the impact of the professional editing of THW on Wikipedia entries. \nWikipedia is not only a source of information. It is also a database: a “cultural form” that one may see as repellent to interpretation and meaning due to its lack of emplotment (Manovich 2001). However, the entire editing history of Wikipedia articles is recorded in its pages. Every change, from a footnote reference to a paragraph modification, is trackable and accessible along with general statistical information provided by the platform. We seek through these data to show three main impacts performed by THW in its edited entries.\nThe first one concerns size in bytes. The edited entries were significantly extended, transforming the amount and quantity of content available to the user. THW sought to edit articles with restricted or outdated content, which led to the reformulation of entries with fewer bytes. “Historicismo” (Historicism) had 5.074 bytes before being redone, and got 97.003 bytes after. There are also cases in which the entries did not exist before, as happened with the “História do Tempo Presente” (History of the Present Time).  \nThe second point concerns pageview increase. A simple before and after comparison shows a significant surge in FA’s number of views. “Scriptorium”, to take one example, had an average of 7 hits per day before being considered a featured article. After the highlight it started to have 33 hits.\nThe third set of data explores a broader universe by looking at the category “Theory of History” as a valuable heuristic tool. Before THW’s intervention, “Teoria da História” on the Portuguese-speaking Wikipedia had 99 categorized entries under its banner. After the intervention of its participants, it was significantly expanded to 262 articles, encompassing new entries and entries not yet categorized.\nMuch of the work on structuring the category data is done manually. Such teamwork helped the Portuguese-speaking Wikipedia to achieve the largest set of entries for Theory of History of all wikis, with 287 entries. But it is not just about quantity. If we look at the featured articles – the platform's gold standard – the Portuguese-speaking Wikipedia, at least in the “Theory of History” category, also has the largest number of awarded entries (7).   \nBut data is not a synonym for evidence. In order to treat computer-processable information as proof, we need first to make sense of it. This process of interpretation treats data as historians have traditionally treated text (Gibbs; Owens 2012). \nThus, in a “hermeneutic” layer, we invite our readers to observe the writing of history on Wikipedia into the larger framework of the information age from the point of view of the experience of time. For doing so, we introduce the theories of social acceleration (Rosa 2013) and Updatism (Pereira & Araujo 2020). Wiki means “fast” and the rise of Wikipedia in itself may be seen as a paragon to the rise of database society. A society in which the question of meaning becomes extraordinarily complex (Nicodemo; Cardoso, 2019, p. 21). \nContrary to traditional encyclopaedias, Wikipedia has been constantly updated. It holds the tools to organize knowledge dispersed on the web as well as to rely on sister projects – such as Wikinews and Wikidata – for doing so. If we still consider the task of the historian as a task to confer meaning to human experience (Ricoeur 1983), Wikipedia’s objective and catalysing language could come as a counterbalance to our “disoriented time” (Hartog 2015)? Or its fragmented, hyperlinked accounts on history serves as primary sources to the understanding of a post digital time regime?    \nAlthough theoretically informed, the hermeneutic layer functions as a driving turnabout leading to the main empirical questions presented here. What aspects have sustained the better performance of the reformulated, featured-awarded articles? Was the higher number of visualizations linked to greater coverage of the entry, be it via Wikipedia “Village pump”, be through THW own promotion? Or was it linked to the fragmented nature of its standardized writing, properly designed to answer specific googled questions? From this set of problems, we also seek to cross-check the collected data with the access data from the platform itself. This transparent approach aims to clarify the methods of discovery underlying our hermeneutic process. Such procedure should allow interpretation to explicate not only its successes, but also its failures (Gibbs; Owens 2012).   \nAt the core of our exploratory inquiry is the question of meaning. And at the core of the question of meaning, we find the topic of narrative (Ricoeur 1983). From a narrativist point of view, we make sense of the world by telling stories about our experience on it. Inspired by this epistemology, we seek to present a “narrative” layer filled with accounts from different online experiences. \nWikipedia is widely used by students and scholars to consult content quickly at no financial cost. To reach this wide audience, we shall begin by using professionals in the field of theory of history and engaging them in a video comparing excerpts from entries written by THW with recognized academic works. In an online quiz, scholars would be asked if the excerpt was taken from Wikipedia or not, adding points to each correct answer.\nIn addition, we also seek to reach teachers. Educators are quite often concerned about the widespread use of Wikipedia by students (Vandendorpe 2015). At this point, we shall ask teachers to summarize a list of concerns regarding Wikipedia. Is the online encyclopedia an undesirable source because it lacks references? Is it seen as unreliable because “everyone” can edit it? Or perhaps it is not the platform itself, but a practice of copy-paste from it that endangers teaching in the post digital era? From the answers we shall provide a top five list of concerns. Then we shall create an online mind map facing the possible threats with tools, rules and solutions provided by Wikipedia and THW own work. At the online map’s center we visualize our ethical goal: education for information.\nWorking with wikipedia may not result in any academic credit, diluted as it is into a “shared authority” (Frisch 1990; Wyatt 2020). Nevertheless, an important part of this story will be told through the voices of those who edited articles through quick and engaging reports. Those testimonies may be centered not only on THW’s achievements, but also on its hardships, limits and frustrations. They will be uploaded via Instagram stories.\nThis way we aim to avoid the creation of an all encompassing “master narrative”, retaining at the same time a common history in our horizon: the very search for historical meaning in the post digital world. \nIt is our conviction that digital evidence is produced through the relationship between interpretation and data (Gibbs; Owens 2012). Thus, our three layers become only possible to unfasten in abstraction. To convey this sense, we welcome transmedia storytelling as a meta-linguistic entanglement perhaps capable of engaging the tension (fundamental for Wikipedia’s historical entries) between narrative and digital databases (Nicodemo; Cardoso, 2019, p. 22). \nReferences\nFrisch, Michael. Shared Authority: Essays on Public History. New York: Sunny University Press, 1990.\nGibbs, Frederick W; Owens, Trevor J. The Hermeneutics of Data and Historical Writing. In: https://writinghistory.trincoll.edu/data/gibbs-owens-2012-spring/ 2012. \nFrançois Hartog. Regimes of Historicity: presentism and experiences of time. New York: Columbia University Press, 2015. \nThiago Lima Nicodemo; Oldimar Cardoso. Metahistory for (Ro)bots: historical knowledge in the artificial intelligence era. História da Historiografia, v. 12, n. 29, p. 17-52, 2019.\nLev Manovich. The Language of New Media. Cambridge: The MIT Press, 2001.\nMateus Pereira; Valdei Araujo. Updatism: Gumbrecht's broad present, Hartog's Presentism and beyond, Diacronie. Studi di Storia Contemporanea: Miraggi e realtà: spazi e tempi della storia, 43, 3/2020. \nPaul Ricoeur. Temps et Récit. Paris: Le Seuil, 1983.\nHartmut Rosa. Social Acceleration – A New Theory of Modernity. New York: Columbia University Press. 2013. \nRoy Rosenzweig. Can history be open source? Wikipedia and the future of the past. The Journal of American History, Bloomington, v. 93, n. 1, p. 117-146, 2006.\nLiam Wyatt. Endless palimpsest: Wikipedia and the future’s historian. Studies in Higher Education. Vol. 45, Num. 5, p. 963-971, 2020.\nChristian Vandendorpe. Wikipedia and the Ecosystem of Knowledge. Scholarly and Research Communication, CISP Press, v. 6, n. 3, p. 1-10, 2015	2020-12-29 02:36:00.684371+00	2021-05-21 15:40:07.467796+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3938-5169	Federal University of Santa Catarina (Brazil) 	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Bonaldo	Rodrigo	ABANDONED	t	\N	4baoPqqf57a8	\N
22	The forgotten Jewish prisoners of the Amersfoort Police Transit Camp 1941-1945.	Bringing names and faces to the numbers assigned to Holocaust victims is the central feature of Holocaust remembrance. This process has been greatly facilitated by digital access to multiple sources and the possibility to combine materials for joint review. However, following the digital turn, academic Holocaust studies remains moored in theoretical exercises, and thus victims continue to be considered largely in abstract terms. Giving them life rests with academics working in the field of remembrance. An example of such efforts can be found in the project War Lives (https://www.oorlogslevens.nl): one million names from some 20 different collections and databases relevant to the Netherlands in World War II were compared using smart algorithms. This approach allowed for the identification and linking of data relating to distinct individuals, resulting in the reconstruction of the lives of nearly 300,000 eyewitnesses to the war. The database includes Dutch people and those living in the Netherlands at the time, some of whom died during the war. \n\nThe proposed article will continue to explore the enormous possibilities and even greater challenges of incorporating this digital public history project, as well as genealogical research, in academic Holocaust studies. As an example of how this works in practice, data from the War Lives project was combined with archival documents from the Arolsen Archives (https://arolsen-archives.org). Through a detailed approach, and the combination of these sources, it was possible to uncover the number of Jewish prisoners who were interned at the police camp Amersfoort and outline their lives before, during, and¬—in a few cases—after the war. This includes the dates of their transportation to Mauthausen and proof of their direct transport from Amersfoort to Auschwitz, for which previously there was no direct evidence. The joint consideration of sources facilitated the identification of the men in these transports and their relationships to one another.\n\nThe full article will present a database, adding theoretical perspectives, and outlining empirical research on the Jews in the Polizeiliches Durchangslager Amersfoort (PDA) in the Netherlands, referred to as the forgotten prisoners. For the first time, an attempt has been made to identify all categories of Jewish prisoners of the PDA by cross-referencing several public remembrance projects. This process has resulted in detailed insights into the role of the Amersfoort camp in the Jewish persecution during the German Occupation of the Netherlands.\n	2020-12-30 09:17:45.25882+00	2021-05-21 15:44:34.697329+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3493-0890	Maastricht University	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Kluveld	Amanda	ABANDONED	t	\N	98X78juYnXkf	\N
23	Making Petro-movies: French industrial films and the creation of the national oil epic (1950s-1980s)	The development of the oil industry has been accompanied by the multiplication of propaganda and corporate communication campaigns. Since their foundation in the 19th century, major oil companies such as Standard Oil have resorted to communication to widespread the myth of black gold and to boost the consumption of refined oil products. In the aftermath of World War II, oil propaganda became a strategic tool which accompanied French oil companies during their quest for national resources. At the beginning of the 1950s, the Compagnie Française des Pétroles (CFP) and the Bureau de Recherches de Pétroles (BRP) produced their firsts films to present their exploration activities in the Sahara and in South West France. Screened in the movie theaters all around the country, French Petro-movies immediately drew the attention of the audience. These productions attracted potential investors and convinced young Frenchmen to join oil companies, to take part in the last chapter of the “French colonial saga” set in the Sahara. During the following decade, decolonization, the 1973 oil shock and the nationalizations announced by OPEC members imposed a major change in oil companies’ strategies, modifying their geographical implantation. Nevertheless, audiovisual communication remains the major tool to present French companies’ implication in the new struggle against energy scarcity as well as their contribution to socio-economic development of oil producing countries. The cooperation with famous filmmakers facilitated the diffusion of new movies presenting French exploration activities in the Far North, in the Northern Sea in Asia and Latin America. From movie theaters to television, the new wave of French Petro-movies contributed to legitimize oil companies’ activities and to foster oil consumption while western government were implementing new energy conservation policies. Situated at the crossroad between energy and cultural history, this paper aims to explain how French Petro-movies contributed to the creation of the national oil epic between the 1950s and 1980s. My research is based on Total audiovisual archives, a collection of films which I have recently digitized, catalogued and integrated in a Digital Asset Management in order to facilitate their preservation and exploitability. Adopting a digital history approach, I would like to present the Compagnie Française des Pétroles communication strategy, integrating in the same support visual information, data and critical analysis of the digital sources from a technical and conceptual point of view. In this sense, the reader will be able to navigate the content and to get a direct access to digitized audiovisual and paper archives while acquiring precise information about the media production context. This system will facilitate the understanding of the research methodology and the interpretation of the sources, offering a dynamic reading experience. Furthermore, this article will contribute to foster the technical reflection about the interconnection between the Journal of Digital History, online video platforms (OVP) and media management tools used by archives, libraries and research institution in terms of accessibility, storage, diffusion and copyrights. \n\n	2021-01-07 15:38:46.33797+00	2021-05-21 15:45:09.858825+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1089-4602	Sorbonne Université - Total Historical Archives	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Mounecif	Radouan	ABANDONED	t	\N	KAB2mBBeuzhJ	\N
24	Charting the Field of Astronomy in Early Modern Europe Using Linked Open Data	In the early Nineties, Richard S. Westfall (1924–1996), a historian of science concerned with the cultural and social context of scientific activity, collected a considerable amount of information about a population of 630 scientists considered to have participated in the Scientific Revolution or in any case deserving of an entry in the Dictionary of Scientific Biography (Charles Gillispie, ed., 1979-1980). The extent of the population was thus defined by the representative character of these scholars from the encyclopedic point of view and brought together representatives from different scientific fields. The analysis of the rich information systematically collected by R. Westfall in different sources, and stored in a local database, allowed him to draw up a first profile of this population —with a primarily heuristic function— in an article published in 1996 [1]. The database was then made available to researchers on a website by Albert Van den Velden [2] and then incorporated into a website published by Robert A. Hatch where it is still available [3]. \n\nThe multiplication of online resources over the last twenty years makes it possible to take Westfall's research agenda into a new dimension, in particular by enlarging the considered population and virtually integrating all the actors who have published works in this field. The starting point of this undertaking will be the bibliographic records of libraries and the correspondent authority files that provide basic information about the authors of the works held by these institutions. In addition, the vision of the LOD [4,5] has led to the linking of these resources through their identifiers or URIs which creates an information graph also involving platforms such as DBPedia, Wikidata, etc. Finally, more and more research projects in humanities and social sciences, particularly in the field of the history of knowledge, are making data available using semantic web technologies and connecting them to identifiers provided by authority files, following the logic of LOD [6, 7]. \n\nFor the digital historian, the challenge therefore becomes to question these resources and to use this data for his/her own research agenda. In this paper, I will present a first stage of this approach using the ‘metadata’ about books and authors present in library authory file records, and show how the information they contain can be collected, wrangled and used to answer research questions. I will focus on a specific discipline, astronomy, and —in the same perspective as Richard Westfall, and considering the same historical period— use this information to ‘chart’ a scientific field, and more specifically the geographical origins of its actors, the places of publication of their books, and also, as far as possible, their places of activity and their evolution in time. I will also inspect the classifications provided by the librarians about books and their authors using a more or less controlled terminology, the co-occurrences of classification terms and their evolution over time with respect to the considered historical object, and, if possible, the networks of relationships emerging from this ‘metadata’. In contrast, the contents of the texts themselves will be left out of scope in this first approach.\n\nThe Thesaurus of CERL (Consortium of European Research Libraries) [8] will be at the heart of this endeavour. It aggregates authority files from several European Libraries, and notably the BNF and GND resources, for the period between 1450 and 1830 [9]. The aggregated data are published as LOD and provide a link to the original resources and external ones. These resources are being parsed and integrated using Python libraries. The methodology adopted will be presented in a series of Jupyter notebooks allowing to follow the process of data recovery, cleansing and integration. In order to combine data stemming from different repositories and data models, a common ontology suitable for intellectual history will be applied, and the data consequently wrangled and published —in the end of the process— in RDF format. Finally, a couple of dedicated Jupyter notebooks will propose a ‘chart’ of the field of astronomy in Early Modern Europe according to the mentioned line of inquiry (geographical mapping, classification, relationships and their and evolution in time) and thus support and accompany the storytelling of the paper that will present a possible model, i.e. a representation of the considered intellectual space from the point of view of the available information.\n\nIt is obvious that this approach raises a whole series of methodological questions that will be partly discussed. Among them two in particular deserve special consideration. In the first place, the available information is produced as metadata of books held in the respective libraries. Is it legitimate to use it for the purpose of scientifically reconstructing the dynamics of an intellectual space? This question applies in particular to the terminologies used to classify works and actors whose purpose is not to account for the historical reality but to summarize the essence of an intellectual profile as perceived today. These resources should therefore be subjected to a critical analysis and compared with more traditional biographical works, on paper [10] or online [11], providing a richer and more complete information.\n\nIn the second place, the available data present a heterogeneity of data models, and possible contradictions and uncertainties. A process of alignment and integration on the base of a common model, resulting from different extensions of CIDOC CRM and publicly documented [12], facilitating the intelligibility and interoperability of the data produced [13], will be carried out and discussed. Also, the data produced and published in RDF format should have a structure that makes it possible to document their origins and inform the alternatives. A discussion of this specific topic will be presented according to an experimental approach, without claiming to provide an answer to this complex question.\n\n\n[1] Richard S. Westfall, « Charting the scientific community », in Trends in the historiography of science, Dordrecht (Kluwer, 1994), 1‑14.\n[2] http://galileo.rice.edu/, cf. https://web.archive.org/web/20070312035700/http://galileo.rice.edu/Catalog/NewFiles/\n[3] http://users.clas.ufl.edu/ufhatch/pages/03-Sci-Rev/SCI-REV-Home/resource-ref-read/major-minor-ind/westfall-dsb/index.htm \n[4] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linked_data\n[5] John Douglas Bradley, « A Prosopography as Linked Open Data: Some Implications from DPRR », Digital Humanities Quarterly 014, no 2 (29 juillet 2020).\n[6] Jörg Wettlaufer et al., « Semantic Blumenbach: Exploration of Text–Object Relationships with Semantic Web Technology in the History of Science », Digital Scholarship in the Humanities 30, no suppl_1 (1 décembre 2015): i187‑98, https://doi.org/10.1093/llc/fqv047.\n[7] Florian Kräutli et Matteo Valleriani, « CorpusTracer: A CIDOC database for tracing knowledge networks », Digital Scholarship in the Humanities 33, no 2 (1 juin 2018): 336‑46, https://doi.org/10.1093/llc/fqx047.\n[8] https://www.cerl.org/resources/cerl_thesaurus/main\n[9] https://www.cerl.org/resources/cerl_thesaurus/contents\n[10] Hockey, Thomas A. Biographical encyclopedia of astronomers. Second ed., 4 vol., Springer Reference. New York: Springer, 2014.\n[11] https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/category-astronomy/\n[12] https://ontome.dataforhistory.org/namespace/11\n[13] Beretta F., A challenge for historical research: making data FAIR using a collaborative ontology management environment (OntoME), Semantic Web, 12/2, 2021 (http://semantic-web-journal.net/content/challenge-historical-research-making-data-fair-using-collaborative-ontology-management-0)	2021-01-27 17:54:46.273131+00	2022-09-22 12:47:43.446871+0