14	‘Murderous, Unwarrantable, and Very Cold’: Killing and Extralegal Violence in the United States, 1783-1865	In the winter of 1862, residents of Nebraska City, Nebraska Territory, killed two alleged horse thieves. The vigilantes executed one man with a shot to the back, and forced the other under the frozen waters of the Missouri river, holding him there until he drowned. The local paper turned the grim scene into a joke, and, in a winking condemnation of the victim being “chucked under the ice,” concluded that the killing was “murderous, unwarrantable, and very cold.” The callous humor is not entirely surprising. Killing, once rare in American extralegal violence, had by the time of the Civil War increasingly emerged as both a powerful tool and a potent ritual in the tradition of “politics out of doors.”\r\n\r\nThis article, “‘Murderous, Unwarrantable, and Very Cold’: Killing and Extralegal Violence in the United States, 1783-1865” uses geospatial and network analysis to investigate and narrate the rise of the use of lethal force within the tradition of extralegal violence in the United States. Rather than a mindless or undirected outburst, extralegal violence is a form of violent social communication in which bodies become both the instruments and the canvas through which a group expresses its aims. A mob’s unsanctioned hanging of a gambler, for example, could not itself end the practice of gambling, but would successfully communicate the mob’s position to authorities, bystanders, and targets. This article argues that many extralegal actors intended for their killings to be witnessed and easily understood, and deliberately imbued their actions with recognizable symbols and references. \r\n\r\nTo interpret the communicative properties of lethal extralegal violence, the data behind this article must be queried not as a series of disconnected flashes, but as a relational phenomenon that draws its strength from a common intelligibility. An approach grounded in digital history offers the unique opportunity to query hundreds of instances of extralegal violence in order to better understand the role that killing played in the early history of American popular crowd action. Geospatial analysis will investigate change over both time and space, moving past the political container of state borders to interrogate local, regional, and national trends within extralegal violence. Network analysis tools will be deployed in order to explore the related attributes of both the sources and targets of violence, emphasizing the interconnectivities present between killings. This approach, focused on group identities rather than individual actors, will help illustrate the relationships and conflicts between various identities at various stages in American history, with special attention paid to race, ethnicity, religion, and political affiliation.\r\n\r\nThe three-layered article structure proposed by the Journal of Digital History is ideal for this submission. Each entry into article’s dataset is equipped with geospatial and temporal information, as well as a description, citation, and a series of attributes tags. Every data point is both a story unto itself, and, when viewed as a collection, a part of larger stories and narratives. This data represents the fundamental building blocks for the article’s approach, and being able to share that data in a transparent way is immensely compelling. In the hermeneutics layer, the article will highlight the process behind identifying the patterns and trends in lethal extralegal action. A central theme of the article’s argument concerns relationships between seemingly disparate or even random violent actions. Spatial and network analysis, made possible by digital tools, is key to spying these relationships and the patterns they create. Data and hermeneutics drive the narration layer. There, the article will combine research-driven argumentation with dynamic storytelling powered by interactive maps and network visualizations. This will enable readers to both focus on individual actions and step back to view the larger pointillist pictures brought into focus when viewing larger sets of the data.	2020-12-15 19:24:43+00	2021-01-07 16:07:33+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2296-7971	University of Nebraska - Lincoln	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Hoehne	Patrick	PUBLISHED	t		8pGzPyTDKBjR	\N
16	The Nameless Crowd: Using Quantitative Data and Digital Tools to Study the Ancient Lexicon of Crowds in Tacitus	Summary\r\n\r\nThe ancient vocabulary of crowds has not sparked much scholarly interest, as has the concept of crowd itself in ancient societies (some exceptions: NEWBOLD 1976, MOUCHOVÁ 1991, BAIER 2010; on the historical level: YAVETZ 1969 or MILLAR 1998). It is usually accepted that words like uulgus, multitudo or turba (in Latin) are vaguely synonymous and refer to the same social reality as populus or plebs do (since YAVETZ 1965, whose conclusions are widely accepted: e.g. VIRLOUVET 1985: 54-63, TONER 2009: 4, COURRIER 2014: 489-497). In this paper, we aim to show that ancient authors, in spite of their contempt towards the lower strata of the society, were completely able to resort to a precise and coherent lexicon when describing, narrating and/or analysing crowd phenomena. The study will focus on the Roman historian Tacitus, whose interest for crowd psychology is a well-known fact (ENGEL 1972). His works (the Annales and the Historiae) are considered astute accounts of the political changes brought about by the new imperial regime, in which crowds (defined as gathering of mainly lower class people outside any traditional institutional context) indubitably gained power and became a central addressee for the emperor and his kin (see VEYNE 1976, FLAIG 1992, COURRIER 2014).\r\n\r\n\r\nHermeneutic Layer\r\n\r\nThe hermeneutic layer will expound on the methodological gap between this paper and the only existing survey of the crowd lexicon in Tacitus (NEWBOLD 1976). This nine-page long study strives to be exhaustive, but fails to allow any data control, since R. F. Newbold only gives numerical totals without specific references to the Tacitean text. The innovative form of the Journal of Digital History allows to claim both exhaustiveness and data-based controllability (see the data layer abstract below). Thus, the first methodological principle will be to take into account every occurrence of the Latin words of the crowd in Tacitus (uulgus, multitudo, turba, uis, coetus) and doing so to embrace a quantitative perspective.\r\n\r\nThe second methodological principle will consist in using digital tools for combinatorial profile exploration based on syntactic dependencies. Building on an earlier phraseological study on the lexicon of crowds in ancient prose writers (AUTIN et al. 2016), we will analyse how a complete, manual survey of these substantives in their Tacitean context supports or disproves the automatic extraction of their most significant collocates and of the colligations related to these collocations. These results will also be compared with those obtained thanks to other lexicometric tools like Hyperbase.\r\n\r\nThe third methodological principle lies in investigating how these linguistic phenomena relate to the social realities they were referring to. Drawing on the recent developments in the social and political history of the Roman Empire, we will take into account the historical context for every occurrence, following three guidelines: a “phenomenological” one (is the crowd described as a spatial phenomenon?), a “sociological” one (what is known of the crowd social composition?) and an “ethological” one (how does the crowd act, demand, protest?). These questions will lead us to investigate the relationship between the vocabulary of the crowd and the institutional vocabulary (populus, plebs), and also to compare Tacitus with other authors from the same period (Suetonius) or with other historiographers (Livy, Ammianus).\r\n\r\n\r\nNarrative Layer\r\n\r\nUnlike most of Latin authors, Tacitus uses predominantly the word uulgus in comparison to turba, multitudo and the other, less frequent nouns referring to urban crowds (see for example Hyperbase data visualisation). This quantitative singularity of uulgus matches the qualitative analysis of the semantic nuances and the contexts of use of these words. Focusing one after the other on our three guidelines (the phenomenological, the sociological and the ethological one, see the hermeneutic layer abstract above) reveals, in a contrastive way, the peculiarity of Tacitus’ uulgus. While turba and multitudo refers to strongly spatialised crowds, whose internal composition does not seem to be a strong defining factor, without any own opinion and with a loose sense of agency, uulgus always refers in Tacitus to a plebeian crowd, defined by its ability to voice its own feelings and/or opinion and to engage in dialogue, or even conflict, with the ruling elites. The lexical polarisation between these nouns is best enlightened when taking into account the semantic traits and colligations of their most frequent collocates: turba and multitudo are often combined as subjects with (mostly prefixed) verbs of movement (adfluere, conglobare, exundare…) or as objects with verbs of dispersion (dimouere, disiicere…), whereas uulgus’ main collocates usually have the semantic traits of /opinion/ (studia, fauor…), /feelings/ (ira, questus…) and /vocalisation/ (rumor, sermo, clamor…). Those words are usually nouns, uulgus being combined with them as a subjective genitive (rumor uulgi, ira uulgi, etc.). Tacitus’ uulgus is thus a crowd which has its own opinion and has the ability of voicing it. In the paper, we will dwell at length on the details of this phraseological and literary analysis, focusing on the most meaningful occurrences. A detailed analysis of Tacitean texts using two or more nouns referring to the crowds (e.g. Tac., Ann., 4.41) will be provided.\r\n\r\nThe second part of the narrative layer will focus on the historical significance of these linguistic conclusions. Vulgus is used by Tacitus, an astute observer of the shifts in the institutions of the res publica Romana during the 1st c. A.D., as a synonym for the more traditional populus or plebs (see e.g. Tac., Ann., 2.41). The uulgus thus seems to become, in Tacitus’ analysis, a new political actor in the imperial regime, an actor which, contrary to the institutional populus, does not express its opinion through the ordinary political institutions that were traditionally controlled by the Roman aristocracy (for example, the voting process), but proceeds to do so through vocalisations in non-institutional (albeit deeply political) contexts: rumours on the streets of Rome, clamours in the theatre or the circus, etc. This shift in the political lexicon is for example revealed in texts like Tac., Hist., 1.72, of which thorough discussion will be given. \r\n\r\n\r\nData Layer\r\n\r\nTwo main sections will be included in the data layer. First, the data obtained with the Lexicoscope tool (corpus exploration tool specially dedicated to the exploration of combinatorial profiles of words or expressions, based on syntactic dependencies – see the methodological layer abstract above), namely lexicosynctatic trees and tables of the most strongly associates collocates of the main collective substantives studied in the paper. Second, a complete table of occurrences of these collective nouns in Tacitus, with both their literary and historical context. This will allow data-based controllability and avoid the usual biases found in earlier studies (which were limited by the traditional, paper-based format), namely selectivity and lack of reusability.\r\n\r\n\r\n--\r\n\r\nBibliography of the abstract\r\n\r\nAutin et al. 2016: L. Autin, K. Bouzidi, O. Kraif & J. Sorba, “Sine nomine uulgus : étude des profils combinatoires des noms de la foule à partir d'un corpus arboré latin”, in D. Mayaffre, C. Poudat, L. Vanni, V. Magri & P. Follett, Statistical Analysis of Textual Data. Proceedings of 13th International Conference on Statistical Analysis of Textual Data. 7-10 June 2016 – Nice, Nice, 2016, p. 389-499\r\n\r\nBaier 2010: T. Baier, “Die Darstellung der Masse in der römischen Literatur”, Aevum, 84, 1, 2010, p. 161-176 \r\n\r\nCourrier 2014: C. Courrier, La plèb