20	Digital history of representations: analysing identity and nationalism in the Capuchin Annual periodical (1930-1977)	Nationalist sentiments formed the basis of the independent Irish state, and, as is often the case in the context of post-colonial countries, its core rhetoric has been accepted in decolonialising national identity agendas. This shared narrative, used by nationalist newspapers and periodicals, has not received enough scholarly attention, especially from an interdisciplinary perspective. This research project offers a case study examining and challenging the attributes of these narrative tropes in an Irish nationalist and religious periodical, the Capuchin Annual. The Capuchin Annual was published in Dublin between 1930 and 1977 by the Capuchin Franciscans, a Roman Catholic order. It was first intended as a religious journal, detailing the history of this order and supporting their missions. Under the influence of Father Senan Moynihan OFM Cap., it quickly took a literary a cultural turn, representing the Irish Roman Catholic intelligentsia in the early decades of the Irish Free State.\nWith a wide readership, estimated at 25,000 both in Ireland and abroad in the 1950s, and with high quality articles, it was considered to be one of the major cultural periodicals of its time in Ireland. Prior to its digitisation, in 2016, it received limited scholarly attention, and no research prior to this research project has been conducted focusing specifically on the content of this periodical. [The digitised periodical was made available online for research use, see http://www.capuchinfranciscans.ie/capuchin-annual-1930-1977/] One of the possible explanations might be the sheer volume of issues published during the 47 years range of this publication, with 44 issues and above 19,000 pages, rendering a thorough analysis difficult on a non-digital source. Its recent digitisation and the access to the digitised and OCRed files granted by the Irish Capuchins’ Provincial Archives, allowed this project to apply corpus linguistic methods to analyse this periodical. This research project aims to analyse representations of Irish nationalist figures in the Capuchin Annual, to understand the impact of the periodical in the configuration of Irish identity and its participation in the writing of an Irish national narrative. To achieve this aim, an interdisciplinary methodology was developed using a combination of history of representations and corpus linguistic methods to analyse the periodical. \nThe publication of the Capuchin Annual situated itself in a post-colonial context, which impacted its views and its representations of nationalism. The Irish Free State was established in 1921, following the War of Independence (1919-1921). However, disagreements over the terms of this independence led to a civil war in 1922 and 1923, which had a long-lasting impact on Irish politics and society. Indeed, the Treaty which signed the end of the War of Independence endorsed the 1920 Government of Ireland Act, which created Northern Ireland and a highly contentious partition. This question of the partition of Ireland was a major nationalist theme, even after 1949, when the Irish Free State became a Republic and won the right to call the country Ireland, which would not be officially recognised by the British establishment until the Good Friday Agreement in 1998. Sectarian language was always used evocatively in the Irish context and following independence, Roman Catholicism was the majority religion in the southern Irish counties. It was integrated into the 1937 Constitution, which officially accorded the Church a ‘special place’ among other religions in Ireland. [Bunreacht na hÉireann, 1937 (Article 44, 1/2).] Although the Catholic hierarchy had an impact on the writing of this Constitution, the Capuchin Franciscans themselves were not directly involved in political actions. The Capuchin Annual, as a religious and cultural periodical, did not originally have a political aim, but it took a nationalist stance from the 1934 issue onward, as Father Senan, who was involved in anti-Partition nationalists’ movements, took more freedom in his editorship. Some of the authors of the periodical were themselves involved in various nationalist movements and Irish politics. Authorship was mainly drawn from the Catholic intelligentsia, as Catholic intellectuals from Ireland and from the diaspora, which held a high role in Irish society at the time. While this nationalist stance was reduced after Father Senan’s departure in 1952, as Father Henry Anglin OFM Cap. took over as editor, it still impacted the periodical until its final edition in 1977. This nationalist narrative, in which the periodical situated itself, had an important impact on the history of ideas in Ireland, as some elements of the current nationalist and far-right discourses, both in Ireland and in its diaspora, originated in this narrative and can be found in the periodical.\nThe hermeneutics layer of this project is based mainly on history and on linguistics, specifically history of representations and corpus linguistics. History of representations here is understood as a ‘social history of cultural representations’, as defined by Pascal Ory in the French historiography. [Pascal Ory, L’Histoire Culturelle (Paris, 2004), p. 13.] The linguistics aspect of the methodology is based on a combination of corpus linguistics and critical discourse analysis, as defined by Paul Baker. [‘Introduction’ in Paul Baker, Tony Enery (eds), Corpora and discourse studies: integrating discourse and corpora (Basingstoke, 2015), pp 4-5.] This methodology led to the creation of a dataset with a main corpus, named the GCA (General Capuchin Annual) corpus, composed of over a thousand articles selected among the 44 issues of the periodical. To allow a detailed analysis on a case study basis, this corpus is divided into sub-corpora selected to analyse specific themes, selected for their connections with the concepts of power, gender, identity and nationalism. In the narrative layer, this article will focus specifically on the case study and sub-corpora analysing the representations of Oliver Cromwell, who was reviled in the Irish historical narrative in which his reputation for atrocity held a high place, as Ireland’s ‘bogeyman’ and as a symbol for English colonisation. [Micheál Ó Siochrú, God’s executioner: Oliver Cromwell and the conquest of Ireland (London, 2008), p. 3.] In this nationalist version of history, the spectre of colonialism with Cromwell as a main character could be used to leverage support for nationalist ideas. The application of this interdisciplinary methodology allows a better understanding of his symbolism in the narrative and of its impact on Irish identity.\nIncluded in this dataset is also a database, comprising the metadata of each article, analysing the presence or absence of a theme, concept, event or figure in the article, among a list of over four hundred criteria. This dataset, combined with the analysis of other digital and non-digital primary sources, allowed a multi-layer analysis of the articles and the nationalist representations they conveyed, and placed them in their broader context. While the research project, and the main corpus, are still a work in progress, the case studies already analysed allowed a global understanding of the views of the periodical and the Roman Catholic intelligentsia in Ireland and in its diaspora, as well as on Irish identity in post-independence Ireland.\nIn its hermeneutic layer, this article will argue that a mixed methodology approach drawing from history of representations, as understood in the French historiography, and corpus linguistics combined, is required to conduct a thorough analysis of digitised cultural sources. It will specifically present a potential methodological pattern for projects aiming to analyse representations of concepts such as power, gender, nationalism and identity, and it will devise a template to re-examine Irish nationalism globally. To do so, it will outline the methodology used in this research project, the theoretical background and the various software and tools used. This article will also examine the limits of this methodology, by presenting the difficulties encountered in this research project, and their potential solutions. Finally, it will present how this hermeneutic layer permitted the analysis of the trans-media narrative of Irish identity. To exemplify this, it will present the narrative of the Cromwell case study. The analysis of this sub-corpus demonstrated how the periodical aimed to unify Ireland around a common hatred of English colonisation, and how specific images, positive or negative, were used to convey ideas and emotions in a readership aware of the sub-text behind these representations. \nThe data layer presented will comprise the Cromwell sub-corpus, a 655,7004 words corpus with 94 cleaned texts annotated with TreeTagger in the TXM software, presented in the XML-TEI format, and its associated metadata in CSV. [Serge Heiden, ‘The TXM Platform: Building Open-Source Textual Analysis Software Compatible with the TEI Encoding Scheme’ in 24th Pacific Asia Conference on Language, Information and Computation (Sendai, 2010), pp 389-398.] The dataset will be composed of the 94 annotated texts in XML, as well as the original texts in TXT format. It will also comprise the separate metadata in CSV and an explanatory file in RTF. It will be available on the Zenodo platform. [The dataset can be sent on request and will be uploaded before publication of the article.] This data layer will allow the reader to refer to specific elements of the dataset, and will also allow them to combine this data with their own to conduct further analyses. \nAs Ireland is working on the decolonisation of its curriculum, this article will argue that digital history methods are necessary to give a better understanding of the impact of nationalist narrative and rhetoric in the formation of its identity and in its perception of history.	2020-12-28 11:57:10.82573+00	2021-01-13 13:33:05.082913+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0635-6935	University of Limerick	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Le Roux	Maelle	PUBLISHED	t	\N	L2gBr3BzwH8Z	\N
19	Topic-specific corpus building: The creation of a representative newspaper corpus on the topic of return migration using LDA and JSD\n	Research question and goal of this paper\nThe advance of digitization also calls for an update of the historical-critical method, the hermeneutical process that promises access to the past through the three steps heuristics, source criticism and interpretation. Especially the second step, the demand for digital source (and it often goes hand in hand with tool criticism) by now is of long standing. Other parts of the historical method, like the relevance and critical assessment of adequate corpus creation in the heuristic research step, have so far not been considered enough. This paper addresses the motivation of corpus building for historical research and asks the question of whether text mining methods can support corpus building in order to distinguish between relevant and non-relevant articles on the topic of return migration. The aim is to highlight the necessity of corpus building and the critical evaluation in the heuristic research step. \n\nNarrative layer\nMotivation: The definition of remigration or return migration is not consistent within research literature. However, all of the explanations of the term have in common that they define return migration as “cross-border migration to the country of origin” (Currle, 2006) or as the return of a person to the country of origin after spending a longer period of time abroad. The return of emigrated people has always been part of every migration movement – also in recent times. Examples include the return from overseas in the 19th and 20th century, the return of war veterans or the repatriation of war refugees during and after the First World War, or the return and repatriation of prisoners of war, refugees, exiles, concentration camp survivors, etc. during and after the Second World War. Historical research on return migration, which is still rare, considers such patterns of, and motivations for, return migration (Wyman, 2001), examines historical, political, sociological or economic backgrounds (Harper, 2012; Olivier, 2013; Poznan, 2017) or deals with autobiographical questions (Prager & Straub, 2017a). So far, however, the complexity and heterogeneity of sources about return migration (e.g. letters, photos, reports, statistical material on return, snippets of personal documentation, interviews, newspaper reporting) has complicated a structured analysis of the topic of return migration. The historical constellations were so diverse that generalizations are difficult to make and thus inherently faulty. What adds to the difficulties is the lack of empirical material. For example, it can still only be roughly estimated how many people who have emigrated voluntarily or involuntarily returned to their home countries (Prager & Straub, 2017b). The compilation of a corpus of empirical material (such as newspaper articles) is therefore still an essential factor if the topic of remigration is to be accessible for research. \nThe problem: The problem when searching for return migration in newspapers, however, is that the topic is difficult to define conceptually and hard, if not impossible, to trace by a simple keyword search alone. There are only a few clear terms such as “Rückkehrer”, “Heimkehrer” or “Rückwanderer” (all German terms for “returnee”) that lead to relevant articles on return migration. Nevertheless, they only cover a small amount of the whole spectrum of return migration articles in newspapers. The combination of keywords that occur together in a defined word distance (e.g. return migrants, returning emigrants, returning home, returning families, return of emigrants) is helpful but error prone. Even if it were possible to cover the topic of return migration in its entirety, many of the word combinations would lead to results that are not relevant. On the other hand, expanding the search by avoiding word combinations and using only typical words in a collection, such as “return” or “returning” on return migration, leads to a considerable number of irrelevant articles. \nWhen building topic-specific text-corpora using queries, there is always a compromise between precision and recall. In other words, there is a conflict between creating a corpus that contains only relevant texts but not all relevant texts available in the entire collection and, on the other hand, creating a corpus that contains all available relevant texts, but at the expense of including many irrelevant texts (Chowdhury, 2010; Gabrielatos, 2007). \nAlready existing methods like Relative Query Term Relevance (RQTR) - a technique to calculate the degree of precision and recall of a query - may be a great help in creating specialized corpora, but they also have their limits. The RQTR method is based on the combination of keywords (candidate term and core query) calculating the relevance of the candidate term (e.g. the relevance of the term Hamas for the topic on refugees). If a candidate term has a clear positive RQTR score, it can add more relevant texts to a corpus. If the score is negative, it would add too much noise to a corpus (Gabrielatos, 2007). This process, however, is highly influenced by the researcher’s choice of candidate terms. Using the context of a search query (in this case the whole content of a newspaper clipping where the keyword appears) to measure the relevance, on the other hand, can make the search less influenced by the researcher's prior knowledge and avoid a too narrow tunnel vision. The question therefore is: Are text mining methods able to distinguish between relevant articles on return migration and non-relevant articles when their only common denominator is the keyword return*?\n\nHermeneutical layer\nThe experiment: In order to use machine learning to support the building of a representative corpus on return migration, this process starts with the creation of a manually annotated training and testing collection - containing relevant as well as non-relevant articles. This step was performed with the beta version of the NewsEye platform. \nLatent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) and the Jensen-Shannon Distance (JSD) have been used to group words and similar expressions that best characterize relevant or irrelevant documents for the topic return migration and to measure the similarity between the topic distribution of an unseen article and the topic distribution of a training corpus. The goal of using this method was to create a topic-specific corpus on return migration, which is representative and can be used for further, qualitative analysis. \nThe combination of LDA and JSD to group similar articles, documents or groups of documents has been described in several research papers (Fothergill et al., 2016; Lu et al., 2019; Niekler & Jähnichen, 2012). What distinguishes our work is the motivation and the new way LDA and JSD were applied. The motivation was clearly to create a representative topic-specific corpus in order to be able answer historical questions. The new approach of using LDA and JSD arose from this necessity and motivation: how can we apply the methods in order to get the best possible results for further qualitative analysis? \nThe Jensen-Shannon distance measures which documents are statistically “closer” (and therefore more alike) by comparing the divergence of their topic distributions. The smaller the distance, the more similar two articles are. Consequently, the topic distribution of each new article (from the test corpus) was compared to the topic distribution of all articles in the trained corpus. A long process of evaluation, reading the results and thinking about new application possibilities followed this work. The found solution was simple and exceedingly successful, but never used in this context so far: For each article in the testing corpus, the ten most similar articles from the training corpus were extracted. These articles carry the information about the manually assigned relevancy. If 60 percent of the automatically found similar articles were annotated as relevant, the new article was marked as relevant, too. Otherwise it was marked as irrelevant.\n \nThe data layer \nFor the training and testing, a collection of 216 article clippings was created manually. After the export of this collection, a Jupyter notebook was used as an environment to combine human-readable narrative with computer-readable code. Using the Python packages Gensim and SpaCy, the collection was preprocessed, i.e. stop words and punctuations were removed, words were stemmed and tokenised. In addition, article clippings that contained less than 30 tokens were removed, since Topic Modeling does not work very well with shorter documents. The notebook was prepared and published in such a way that other researchers (especially humanities scholars) can also apply the method to their own data.\n	2020-12-27 20:35:18.328114+00	2020-12-29 14:59:56.804823+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1031-2759	Universität Innsbruck	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Oberbichler	Sarah	PUBLISHED	t	\N	4yxHGiqXYRbX	\N
12	International Migration Management and Technocracy	1. Topic\r\n\r\nThe scholarly debate on international migration has been characterized over the past 30 years by a focus on globalization and a paradigm shift to the study of migration management. The key actors in migration management are the nation states and also the international meetings and organisations consisting of trained experts. They have become more and more the subject of current discourses around the legitimacy of technocratic governance. In this article we will historicize the concept of migration management and investigate the connections between technocratic experts and one of today’s biggest players in the international field, albeit a fairly contested one: the International Organisation for Migration (IOM). We do this by operationalizing the concept of discourses coalitions.  \r\n\r\n2. Publication Layers\r\n\r\n2.1 Narrative Layer\r\nThe current activities of the IOM with regard to the regulation of migrant flows is not undisputed. In particular, the ‘voluntary’ return programs appear to be subject to criticism. Geiger and Koch (2018) conceptualize the ‘intergovernmental’ IOM as a ‘world organization’ as IOM has relations with both state and non-state actors, such as NGOs or civil society. This, they argue, makes it possible to analyze which actors participate in the decision-making process, how they participate, and with what authority. Although they suggest to describe IOM’s history from the start in 1951 (with the constitution of its predecessor PICMME), in fact they directly jump to the mid 1980s, thus leaving its historical roots understudied (but see Parsanoglou and Tourgeli 2017), and especially IOM’s technocratic character (p.39). Especially the constitutive years of ICEM are key to understanding how and which actors from both science and politics were able to be of influence on ICEM’s decision-making processes. By using the concept of discourse coalitions – defined by Wagner (as cited in Raphael 2012) as constellations at any given time in which social scientists develop ideas ‘that strengthen the arguments of a group of actors in the political system, whose policies might, in turn, support the standing of these scientists in academia’ –  we are able to lay bare networks of technocrats (on basis of their publications) shaping migration management interactively with national governments.  \r\n\r\nWe address the following main research questions:\r\n- What is the connection between the Intergovernmental Committee for European Migration (ICEM) (and its successor IOM) and the Research group for European Migration Problems (REMP)? \r\n- Can REMP be seen as the informal discourse coalition which formed the nexus between science and politics in what nowadays is called ‘migration management’? \r\n- How did this supposed discourse coalition develop through time and how can this be explained?\r\n\r\nTo address these broad research questions, we analyse a large set of publications of these organisations and use digital methods to zoom in on the actors in these coalitions and the topics \r\n- Sub RQ 1: Who were the key scientists involved, and who were the key political actors?\r\n- Sub RQ 2: How were they connected to the key political actors and institutions mentioned above?\r\n- Sub RQ 3: How did the topics of this discourse develop?\r\n\r\n2.2 Hermeneutic / Processing Layer\r\n\r\nIn the hermeneutic layer, we reflect on the methods we used and how this has shaped our interpretations and insights, as well as the considerations and decisions for selecting and leaving out resources. The main question we address here is:\r\n\r\n- Why and how do the data support our story?\r\n- Why and how do we combine analog and digital research?\r\n- How robust are our choices for processing and visualising the data?\r\n\r\n \r\n2.2.1 Selection of sources\r\n\r\nFor the analysis we used the articles published in the REMP publications, the REMP Bulletin (1951-1962) and the International Migration bulletins (1961-1990). For the word clouds and topical analysis, we use the titles of the articles. For the network analysis of actors, we extracted the names of authors, editors, funders and others from prefaces and introductions to journal editions.\r\n\r\nTo investigate the discourse coalitions, we started from the IOM and working our way back to earlier organisations and publications, we stumbled on a central figure in the coalition, Gunther Beyer. Through further investigation we found several journals on international migration in which he played a central role. Key points we discuss here are:\r\nthe choices and selection of information layers extracted from sources,\r\nthe completeness of the set of relevant publications we found and the consequences of missing publications for the structure of the networks and the word clouds,\r\nthe availability of metadata in online catalogues like WorldCat.\r\n\r\n2.2.2 Data processing and analysis\r\n\r\nTo elaborate the data processing and analysis, the discussion comprises:\r\n- the translation of the research question to queries of the data sources using the Data Scopes framework (Hoekstra & Koolen 2019),\r\n- the analysis and combination of various data sources to (partial) answers to the research questions,\r\n- which ‘tools’ we used and what parameters and configurations (notebooks, scripts, visualization software etc),\r\n- the choices for making the topical and network visualisations,\r\n- a robustness analysis of our chosen methods. The key point of this is to demonstrate how different choices for visualising the topical analysis and the actor networks affect the visualisations and what they highlight, but at the same time that small differences in choices all result in the same interpretations.\r\n\r\nThis will be presented via a Jupyter notebook to allow replication of the analysis and visualisation, as well as to investigate alternative choices. For instance, for the discourse networks, we include a dynamic network visualisation that redraws the network for a sliding 10-year window over the entire period. In the notebook, readers can change the size of the window to show how different period lengths affect the networks.\r\n\r\n3. Data Layer\r\n\r\nIn the data layer we describe the resources we have used, including both digital and analogue resources. Our research resulted in the construction of two data sets, each based on metadata and information extracted from close reading of one or more journal series on international migration.\r\n\r\n- Data set 1 (for the network analysis): REMP publications 1-20 (books), REMP Bulletins (1952-1960), and additional series (by Gunther Beyer). \r\n\r\n- Data set 2 (for the content analysis of the discourse): International Migration Magazine (all articles published in the period 1961-1990)\r\n(continuation and extension of REMP from 1961)\r\n\r\nThis is based on the following WorldCat identities:\r\n- REMP: https://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n50070935/\r\n- ICEM: https://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n50055088/\r\n- IOM: https://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-no90018047/\r\n\r\n4. References\r\n\r\nFaassen, M. van, & Hoekstra, F. G. (2017). Modelling Society through Migration Management: Exploring the role of (Dutch) experts in 20th century international migration policy. . Paper presented at Government by Expertise, Amsterdam, Netherlands.\r\n\r\nGeiger M & Koch M (2018) “World Organizations in Migration Politics: The International Organization for Migration”. Journal of International Organizations Studies (JIOS) 9(1): 23-42\r\n\r\nHoekstra, F. G., Koolen, M., & van Faassen, M. (2018). Data scopes: towards transparent data research in digital humanities. Digital Humanities 2018 Puentes-Bridges.\r\n\r\nKoolen, M., Kumpulainen, S., & Melgar-Estrada, L. (2020, March). A Workflow Analysis Perspective to Scholarly Research Tasks. In Proceedings of the 2020 Conference on Human Information Interaction and Retrieval 