49	Designing Our Digital Past: Anchoring Digital-History Tool Development in the Historical Method Through Design-Based History Research	Many of the tools digital humanists use have come from a variety of disciplines outside of history. As a consequence, many digital-history methods sections focus on how a tool developed by non-historians might support, or need to be adapted for, particular historical questions. Few digital tools have been developed by and for historians with a specific eye to the methdological and theoretical explorations of design principles that anchor digital-history-specific tool development in historiographic practices.\r\n\r\nThis article introduces Design Based History Research (DBHR) as a methodological bridge between the practices of digital-history tool design, the use of digital methods to create historical argumentation, and social-science-inspired methodological innovation. Design Based Research (DBR) is an approach to the study of learning theory that integrates theory into a design, implements the design, and then studies the design as a way of modifying both the theory and the design that aims to reify it. DBHR is an adaptation of the DBR approach grounded in the unique needs of historians and the historical method. \r\n\r\nWe aim to illustrate DBHR by describing the design and use of Net.Create, an open-source user-focused network-analysis tool that prioritizes historiographic practices (evidence interpretation, citation preservation, and historiographic debate) in its feature development and user-interface choices. In the narrative layer, we document how the needs of digital historians shaped the current design of Net.Create, and in the hermeneutic layer, we explore the connections between specific tool features and their operation, and how those tool features support the digital-history needs we identified.\r\n\r\nWe will then extend the narrative, supported by the data layer, to present individual instances of human-computer-interaction analysis and user-entered network data that shaped each stage of our feature development around digital history practices: simultaneous data entry supports historiographic debate; revision of network taxonomy and network data in an easy-to-use interface to support interpretation and reinterpretation of evidence by many collaborators simultaneously; and data provenance features that expose each researcher's positionality and preserve the original citations for each network datapoint to support the integration of close-reading analytical practices. We will describe each development stage in the narrative layer and use the data layer to present user-behaviors, log files, and user-generated network data that allowed us to evaluate how effectively our digital-history tool-design choices supported the historiographic practices we identified as important to the practice of collaborative digital history.\r\n\r\nIn the process of this study, we aim to shape the future of digital-history tool-building research through the articulation of concurrent and intertwined development of historical theory, digital-history tools, and collaborative historical methods.	2022-10-22 15:20:26+00	\N	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-8909-0369	Indiana University Bloomington	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Craig	Kalani	ACCEPTED	t	https://github.com/kalanicraig/dbhr_jdh2023/blob/master/work/author_guideline_template.ipynb	BGU3PDv9p7pC	2
54	Towards a generic base model for Swedish historical handwritten text	The archives contain large amounts of handwritten source material from the Middle Ages to the present day. These written sources are the foundation of our knowledge of history. They are also essential for genealogy and local heritage studies – two popular movements that involve citizens all over Sweden. The ability to research and use these sources is greatly enhanced when the content is transcribed and searchable. However, reading and interpreting handwritten texts is difficult and time-consuming. Artificial intelligence (AI) is now radically changing the conditions, as computers can be trained to automatically interpret handwritten texts, known as Handwritten Text Recognition (HTR).\r\n\r\nHTR is trained using manually transcribed text pages (ground truth). About 50 manually transcribed text pages are required to machine read a specific collection (see e.g. https://readcoop.eu/transkribus/wiki/model-training/). However, our experience shows that up to 200 manually transcribed pages may be required to get below a 5% character error rate (CER) on the word level, which is desirable if the machine interpretation is supposed to be accurate. The great value of HTR technology, therefore, applies to large collections, and texts with similar content, such as court books och other state archives.\r\n\r\nOne way to reduce the need for training data is to use base models. This means that a new model gets knowledge from an existing model. Ideally, a base model should apply to many different types of material, from different periods and with different writing styles. Not least, the workflow would be facilitated if proven base models were available when new specialized models are trained.\r\n\r\nIn this paper, we investigate how a base model can be created for handwritten texts in Swedish. Five existing datasets of ground truth are combined; in total around 1000 manually transcribed text pages from the period c. 1650–1900. These five datasets represent different domains within the state archives (e.g. court records, police reports, travel reports, and similar).\r\n\r\nWith this, we want to answer two questions: First, how well does a base model generalize to other domains? For example, how much better will text recognition be if training data from a new domain is added to the base model? Second, how well does a base model generalize over time? For example, how does an 18th-century model perform against 19th-century text and vice versa, and how much better or worse does the base model get when texts from different periods are added? We will evaluate the various experimental HTR models we are creating, to point out the direction of how a large base HTR model for handwritten texts in Swedish can be trained.\r\n\r\nThe ground truth data are in the PAGE XML format. We will first train a segmentation model by using  MMDetection, an open-source object detection toolbox (https://github.com/open-mmlab/mmdetection). A text recognition model is then trained using MMOCR, based on PyTorch, an open-source machine learning framework (https://github.com/open-mmlab/mmocr). We here choose an attention-based OCR/HTR architecture called Self-Attention Text Recognition Network (SATRN, https://arxiv.org/abs/1910.04396). Our HTR base model will be marked as Creative Commons CC-BY, and the source code for our workflow will be open source and can be presented in a Jupyter Notebook.	2022-10-31 21:27:49+00	\N	https://orcid.org/0000-0003-4350-7533	The Swedish National Archives	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Karsvall	Olof	ACCEPTED	t		cqUDx92E7RmR	2
52	A Digital Toolbox for Studying the LGBTQ World, 1965-1990	Mapping the Gay Guides (MGG) relies on Bob Damron’s Address Books, an early but longstanding travel guide aimed at gay men since the early 1960s. An LGBTQ equivalent to the African American “green books,” the Damron Guides contained lists of bars, bathhouses, cinemas, businesses, hotels, and cruising sites in every U.S. state, where gay men could find friends, companions, and sex. The online mapping project explores different dimensions of American gay life through time, from bars and nightlife, bookstores, cinemas, and churches. The project website includes a visualization that relies on ArcGIS’s API to host the data and on web-based mapping technologies (Leaflet) to map and visualize all 60k+ entries in Damron’s Guides between 1965 and 1985. Users to the site are able to navigate and investigate the dynamic and sometimes disappearing nature of LGBT spaces over time. \r\nBy associating geographical coordinates with each location mentioned within the Damron Guides, MGG provides an interface for visualizing the growth of queer spaces in the United States. MGG’s interactive web app includes a series of filters that can be used to interact with the digitized data including narrowing the data down by city or state, or choosing to display only certain categories of establishments. \r\n\r\nThese guides contain a wealth of information about LGBTQ life in the 1960s, 70s, and 80s but MGG’s web map is only one tool for analyzing this data. Listings in the Damron Guides are grouped by state and then by city. A typical entry in the guide includes the name of the establishment, an address, sometimes notes or warnings, and often an “Explanation of Listings” which were lettered designations describing Damron’s categorization of the location. For example, a location may contain “(AYOR)” next to it indicating that it is a dangerous location and that one should visit it “at your own risk.” Often, Damron listed numerous categories for a single entry. While mapping allows an analysis of where these locations appeared, more sophisticated questions can be asked by using tidy data tools to examine patterns in these categorizations. MGG is in the process of developing an R data package that gives users access to the raw Damron Guide data but also to a series of filters and functions that allow users to query the data and ask more sophisticated questions. This article will focus on MGG as a digital tool for research and will use case studies to investigate the types of historical questions that can be asked of the map and the data package. Our specialized digital toolbox, composed of a web-based map and a R data package, offers two distinct pathways for scholars to engage with the world that Damron described in his LGBTQ travel guides. In accordance with the Journal of Digital History’s format, this article will have a narration, hermeneutic, and data layer focused on exploring MGG as a tool for digital research.	2023-03-16 15:20:08+00	\N	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4260-5839	Clemson University	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Regan	Amanda	PUBLISHED	t	https://github.com/regan008/mggjdh	X3MGSKqAycaT	2
