71	History of fandoms: cyber communities and their evolution (1996-2020)	The article is devoted to the evolution of fandoms on the Internet. The modern world lives in a mode of constant connectivity and communication. The active development of digital technologies, the emergence of new opportunities for communication leads simultaneously to the availability and dissemination of mass culture and the possibility of immersion in it. These radically change the cultural sector. Emerging fan cultures consume and create their own digital content. \r\nContemporary historical research mostly concerns the development of individual fandoms and their general historical significance (Hills, 2002; Reagin and Rubenstein, 2011). The fandom cybercommunities is a relatively new area for studying on the basis of materials from web archives. It is important to raise the questions about the perception of fandom as a digital community and the transformation of fandom culture to understand this cultural phenomenon. The article addresses these issues and draws conclusions about the significance and development of fandom culture from the 1990s to the present. \r\nThe study of fandoms is based on the methodological framework proposed by Kristina Busse for the study of online fandoms (Busse, 2006). The historical analysis has been conducted using a database. It organizes information about the name of the fandom, the year of its creation, the platforms created, the period of its functioning (maximum and minimum), the audience, reflect other attributes of the development of fandoms over time, its main directions, etc. Sixty websites of fans creativity from the Open Doors project were selected for analysis (Open Doors, 2022). The compilation was created by fans dedicated to providing storage to fan content at risk. For the current study, a set of fandoms were selected that communicate in Russian and English languages. All the selected websites are preserved in the Internet Archive and the snapshots were involved in the analysis.\r\nBased on the data from the web archives, it is possible to conduct a quantitative and qualitative analysis of fandom communities, identify certain patterns of development inherent in the fandom community and trace the dynamics of the development of fandoms and their sites, as well as the dependence on topics and their diversity.\r\nThe results of the investigation have shown the following. Since the 1990s, there has been a constant increase in the number of users creating and consuming fandom culture. Digital technologies have significantly transformed fandoms. Since early 2000s, the role of multi-fandom venues and crossover works has been increasing; the subcultures of role-playing and fandom players have been interpenetrating. It is also observed that with the development of technology, the language barrier is also moving away. In addition, there is a gradual identification of many legal problems, among which the problem of copyright is particularly acute. A separate direction is the parallel development of fandoms and queer currents. All of these outcomes will be addressed in the paper in more details.\r\nIt is concluded that the history of fandom cyber communities is an important topic with broad prospects for development in various directions - from history of the interaction of fandoms and consumer culture to history of the interrelationships of the development of fandoms and the history of minorities.\r\nReferences\r\n\r\nBrügger N. The web as history: Using web archives to understand the past and the present. UCL Press: University College London. London, 2017.\r\nBusse K. Fan Fiction and Fan Communities in the Age of the Internet: New Essays, 2006. \r\nCaplan D. Why Would Any Woman Want To Read Such Stories? The Distinctions between Genre Romances and Slash Fiction // Frantz S., Selinger E. (Eds.) New Approaches to Popular Romance Fiction. Jefferson, NC: McFarland, 2012. Pp. 121–132.\r\nClick M.A., Scott S. (Eds.) The Ro