72	In search of an interpretative environment for digital traces: the building of Arvest	MemoRekall-IIIF: an open-source IIIF video annotation tool for exploring historic audiovisual source materials\r\n\r\nPart of a centuries-old history of a “close reading” approach, annotation contributes to the redocumentarization of digital traces, be they born digital or digitized, their semiotization, and their preservation. Audiovisual sources are one of the most complex traces to deal with because they require a temporal dimension to the usual spatial dimension of annotating. In addition, they need multiscale and multimodal environments. During the last decade, different teams created tools to annotate video recordings, especially for sports or social science analysis. Some of them are twisted for historical research. \r\n\r\nThe article starts with a state-of-the-art review of 28 video annotation tools. Then, the evaluation focuses on a dozen characteristics that we shall expect from those tools, such as: (1) supported storage/streaming services, (2) annotation modalities, (3) cooperation features, (4) sharing capabilities, (5) interoperability, (6) extensibility, (7) local vs. online usage, (8) business model, (9) governance, etc. The review shows that, despite some inspiring features, all the considered pieces of software present important drawbacks. The main problems we identified are the lack of interoperability and extensibility, which prevents nearly any kind of incremental and open research. \r\n\r\nOpen Source tools, built on standard formats and API, are a sound way to ensure interoperability, re-usability of annotated content, and extensibility with new features. Therefore, we present in the second part our ongoing effort to develop MemoRekall-IIIF, a document and video annotation framework with virtuous characteristics such as being: modular, open source, and based on the IIIF open standard (https://iiif.io/). This project aims to provide an extensible software 