30	Editorial first issue of the Journal of Digital History	On pyramids and prisms\r\n\r\nIn a 1999 review essay for the New York Review of Books entitled “The New Age of the Book”, the distinguished historian Robert Darnton at that time acting president of the American Historical Association sketched his vision of a new form of historical scholarship, being able to make new sense of evidence, historical argumentation, and analysis by producing new formats of digital storytelling and narration. Rebutting the popular predictions of the death of the book, Darnton advocated for new forms and formats of electronic publishing, structuring scholarly information and interpretation in a layered manner “arranged like a pyramid”:\r\n\r\n“The top layer could be a concise account of the subject, available perhaps in paperback. The next layer could contain expanded versions of different aspects of the argument, not arranged sequentially as in a narrative, but rather as self-contained units that feed into the topmost story. The third layer could be composed of documentation, possibly of different kinds, each set off by interpretative essays. A fourth layer might be theoretical or historiographical, with selections from previous scholarship and discussions of them. A fifth layer could be pedagogic, consisting of suggestions for classroom discussion and a model syllabus. And a sixth layer could contain readers' reports, exchanges between the author and the editor, and letters from readers, who could provide a growing corpus of commentary as the book made its way through different groups of readers.”	2021-09-27 13:21:10+00	2021-09-27 13:23:30+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0237-2532	C2DH	frederic.clavert@uni.lu	Clavert	Frédéric	PUBLISHED	t		jXupS3QAeNgb	\N
29	Taking the Measure of Social Democracy: Exploring the Ideology of the Socialist International through Topic Modelling	The role of European social democracy in the origins of the Cold War is a key question for its history, with a rich literature behind. However, combining digital history with transnational approach can still produce new insights into the subject. The rarely explored Socialist International offers the best opportunity to experiment with new tools. \r\nThis article explores the political culture of European social democracy at the beginning of the Cold War by analysing the debates inside the Socialist International to define a socialist identity. The organisation, to which most European socialists belonged, allowed them to coordinate their activities and reach an agreement on ideas and strategy through debate. For this purpose, the Socialist International published a journal in the late 1940s and a book in the early 1950s, to which most parties contributed articles or chapters. These collections are representative of the political culture of European social democracy at the time, so they provide a great opportunity to analyse the transnational circulation of ideas. In the era of mass parties, examining the ideology of few great thinkers or top leaders is not enough; political culture is better expressed by myriads of speeches and articles produced by low-ranking party officials and journalists as well. A comprehensive analysis is beyond traditional textual analysis, but digital history is particularly suited for this purpose, as quantitative text analysis can reveal hidden similarities and underlying tensions within social democratic culture. \r\nThis article relies on new data specifically digitised for this article: the texts produced by the Socialist International for the large public from the late 1940s to the mid-1950s. While it is a small corpus, it is comprehensive and representative of most social democratic parties across Europe. The possibility of combining close and distant reading allows to test which instruments of corpus linguistics are best suited to study political culture of mass movements. This article employs topic modelling to reveal not just what were the main interests and concerns of social democrats at the time, but also differences among parties and the existence of subgroups within the socialist family. The results will allow to enrich the narrative of how European social democracy acted at the beginning of the Cold War, from the descent of the Iron Curtain, to the intense bipolar tension to the first steps in decolonisation and European integration.	2021-05-25 22:47:11+00	2021-07-01 08:00:08+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0037-3742	Centre for European Research, University of Gothenburg	elisabeth.bguerard@uni.lu	Costa	Ettore	PUBLISHED	t		MyifnvNPDgUx	\N
37	Social Histories and Code Archives: The History of Digital Humanities on Github	Since its launch in 2008, Github, the collaborative version control platform, has become popular among software companies and digital scholars alike. From Jason Heppler’s Rubyist Historian[i] to the multilingual publication of the Programming Historian,[ii] Github has become the platform for the digital humanities community to share everything from large scale projects to individual research and syllabi.\r\n \r\nThis article proposes an in-depth study of digital humanists' use of Github. We seek to understand how this platform functions as a space for DH knowledge production and community and represents new opportunities and challenges for digital historians’ use of web archives. We explore how Github provides an alternative to citation or Twitter networks for exploring DH.[iii] Who exactly is coding in DH? Are most scholars working collaboratively or individually? What patterns have emerged on this platform since the first repository was tagged as “digital-humanities”?[iv] We believe these questions help reformulate Github not simply as a version control platform, but also as a space for exploring the social history of coding in DH.\r\n \r\nThere have been studies of the digital humanities community on Github before, notably the work of Lisa Spiro and Sean Morey Smith in 2015.[v] Using surveys of DH community members with Github profiles, this qualitative study provides useful context, but tells only part of the story. Github itself has also been the focus of a number of computational studies, though these largely have been premised on either building recommendation systems or assessing the quality of code contributions.[vi] While we draw from this research, as well as the rich scholarship on web archiving[vii] and increasingly on social media archives,[viii] we believe that Github has been under-examined as a digital archive, especially considering the platform’s Arctic Code Vault initiative, which will likely become some of the best preserved code archives of our era.\r\n \r\nTo uncover this history, our paper comprises three layers. The first narrative layer will detail the social history of DH through the lens of the Github platform. The hermeneutic layer will demonstrate our methods for aggregating and connecting the projects, users, and works that are accessible through the Github API. To identify this data, we selected all repositories with the topic of digital humanities, and then use a combination of the Python libraries, such as Pandas, Altair, networkx, and scikit-learn, for data analysis and visualization, to uncover both the shape of the DH network on Github and explore what features distinguish participation in this community. The third layer of the project in its own (meta) Github repository is the relevant code, as well as the code for data collection, documented Jupyter notebooks, and curated datasets. With this approach we believe we can reveal the breadth of DH coding communities and consider when and why users participate in DH.\r\n \r\nIn studying the DH community on Github, we are not making claims about all of DH or revisiting previous debates about whether coding is a necessary component of being a digital humanist. Rather, we are interested in exploring the dynamics within this under-examine subset of the DH community, looking at individual, as well as large scale projects to begin to talk about the (often uncredited or invisible) realities of digital work in the humanities.\r\n\r\n\r\n[i] Heppler began publishing The Rubist Historian on Github in 2010. https://github.com/hepplerj/rubyist-historian\r\n[ii] Programming Historian is currently the top starred repository on Github that is tagged as “digital-humanities” with 461 stars https://github.com/programminghistorian/jekyll. Starring a repository is similar to liking a tweet or Facebook post, for more information see https://docs.github.com/en/get-started/exploring-projects-on-github/saving-repositories-with-stars#about-stars.\r\n[iii] For examples see, Gao, Jin, Julianne Nyhan, Oliver Duke-Williams, and Simon Mahony. "Gender influences in Digital Humanities co-authorship networks." Journal of Documentation 78, no. 7 (2022): 327-350 and Grandjean, Martin. "A social network analysis of Twitter: Mapping the digital humanities community." Cogent Arts & Humanities 3, no. 1 (2016): 1171458.\r\n[iv] Porphyry by Hypertopic is the oldest repository that has the tag “digital-humanities” https://github.com/Hypertopic/Porphyry and was initially created on February 3, 2011. Since 2017, Github has allowed users to tag their repositories with topics https://github.blog/2017-01-31-introducing-topics/.\r\n[v] Spiro, Lisa, and Sean Morey Smith. “Evaluating Github as a Platform of Knowledge for the Humanities,” Krakow, Poland, 2016. https://digitalscholarship.files.wordpress.com/2016/07/spirosmithdh2016githubpresentationfinal.pdf.\r\n[vi] For examples of studies more focused on the social coding dynamics of Github, see: Tsay, Jason, Laura Dabbish, and James Herbsleb. "Influence of social and technical factors for evaluating contribution in GitHub." In Proceedings of the 36th international conference on Software engineering, pp. 356-366. 2014; Kalliamvakou, Eirini, Georgios Gousios, Kelly Blincoe, Leif Singer, Daniel M. German, and Daniela Damian. "The promises and perils of mining github." In Proceedings of the 11th working conference on mining software repositories, pp. 92-101. 2014; and Dabbish, Laura, Colleen Stuart, Jason Tsay, and Jim Herbsleb. "Social coding in GitHub: transparency and collaboration in an open software repository." In Proceedings of the ACM 2012 conference on computer supported cooperative work, pp. 1277-1286. 2012. For computational studies, see Ray, Baishakhi, Daryl Posnett, Vladimir Filkov, and Premkumar Devanbu. "A large scale study of programming languages and code quality in github." In Proceedings of the 22nd ACM SIG