43	‘Thanks for the moan!’ Disillusionment with the British sickness system, online and in print, 1997–2005	The turn of the millennium saw significant shifts in British social security and employment policy for sick and disabled people. On the one hand, European and anti-discrimination laws gave individuals greater protections. On the other, active-labour-market policies from the in-coming Labour government restricted access to disability-related social security; while employers were becoming increasingly concerned with how to manage absenteeism as flexible and “lean” employment practices led businesses to become even more intolerant of employees taking sick leave. Web archives offer a useful window onto how British citizens understood these processes. Workers who directly experienced sickness systems left evidence of their opinions on blogs and message boards. But so too did middle managers, as well as friends and relatives of those who had to negotiate sickness-related bureaucracies.\r\n\r\nThis article combines evidence from the Internet Archive with journal articles, newspapers, and government procedural papers to show how New Labour’s sickness and disability policies fit within the longer history of the British welfare state. By adding archived web pages to the “traditional” sources in the writing of political, social, and cultural histories of Britain, it argues that new insights can be gained not just on how citizens experienced the welfare state but also how they understood changes relative to a remembered past. It argues that while the decline of trade union membership, secure employment, and access to social security reduced citizens’ power relative to their employers and the government, activity on the web suggests that workers were through their online activity simultaneously more able to publicly express their frustrations, share advice, and get access to services that could help them navigate their rights under employment law.\r\n \r\nDespite the richness of these sources, however, they must be read critically and with methodological care. The search techniques used here to access blogs and message boards provided many examples of citizen engagement with sickness systems on the .uk top-level domain. But these were necessarily a fraction of all utterances about sickness that would have been made at the time. Furthermore, while historical actors “published” their thoughts by volunteering information on the public internet, they had no reasonable expectation that their messages would be held for so long in an archive – or that they might realistically be read by a wide audience, mediated through an academic paper. At the very least, this paper discusses citizens’ writings about their experiences without informed consent. The article thus concludes with discussion of these methodological considerations and why it remains important to “triangulate” with non-web-archival evidence, especially for the early mass-web-usage period.	2022-05-18 13:19:03+00	2022-06-21 13:20:19+00	https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2833-0442	DIAS, University of Southern Denmark	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Millward	Gareth	ACCEPTED	t		7XSDVCtnbXva	1
45	How do we avoid the loss of our digital memory? Challenges for the archiving (and analysis) of social media content [Working title]	The technological transformation has not only digitised historical sources, but also generated past-related born-digital data. This is especially true for social media. The low production barriers and wide-ranging access options have multiplied content, actors and media practices which challenge the interpretative and discursive authority of established actors such as institutions or researchers. This offers opportunities, especially for previously marginalised stories or groups, but at the same time also leads to challenges in the form of historical revisionism, fake news or hate speech. \r\n\r\nSocial media nowadays function as an important space for history education, but they also provide an insight into discourses and practices related to the past. They show what ideas people have about history and how narratives are (re)produced and discursively negotiated. Examples such as @realDonaldTrump on Twitter or protest movements like #BlackLivesMatter or #CzarnyProtest also highlight the importance of social media data as sources for contemporary history. \r\n\r\nFrom a research(er’s) perspective social media therefore function not only as a sphere of action, but also as an archive. The connection of narratives and media to (big) data structures and global companies, however, leads to technical, ethical and legal challenges. This concerns the accessibility and archivability of audiovisual social media, when platforms like Instagram or TikTok only provide limited APIs or completely prohibit automated data collection. In just a few decades, historians will not be able to write contemporary history without social media data. However, there is still a lack of extensive archiving of data and of skills in dealing with social media (data). \r\n \r\nIn our contribution we want to reflect on Instagram and TikTok as historiographical sources and also performative archives. \r\nIn this light, five dimensions can be identified that historians have to deal with when researching history on social media: the technical dimension (1), the legal dimension (2), the data protection dimension (3), the ethical dimension (4) and the empirical dimension (5). Especially the first and the last dimension require cooperation with digital humanities scholars, who are able to provide solutions to technical challenges that arise from the historians' questions and needs. \r\n \r\nWe plan to exemplify the five identified dimensions with two use cases that we are studying in our project "SocialMediaHistory – History on Instagram and TikTok". \r\nThe selected examples @ichbinsophiescholl (Instagram) and @heeyleonie (TikTok) represent different types of actors and are at the same time the most popular and widest-reaching German past-related accounts on the respective platforms.\r\nWe will show which hurdles have to be overcome to archive and even more to analyse the content of these platforms. For legal reasons, it will not be possible to publish the data we are gathering. Instead, we will publish the code (as Jupyter notebooks) with which the data collection (on the current websites of the platforms) can be reproduced and discuss to what extent it can be adapted to future versions of the websites and other services as long as they don’t have a public API.\r\n\r\nBibliography (selection): \r\nJünger, Jakob (2021):  “A brief history of APIs. How social media providers shape the opportunities and limitations of online research”, in: Engel, U/Quan-Haase, A/Liu, S X/Lyberg, L. (Hgg.), Handbook of Computational Social Science (S. 17-32). London: Routledge. doi: 10.4324/9781003025245-3.\r\n\r\nKönig, Mareike (2017): “Digitale Methoden in der Geschichtswissenschaft. Definitionen, Anwendungen, Herausforderungen”, in: BIOS – Zeitschrift für Biographieforschung, Oral History und Lebensverlaufsanalysen 1-2 (S. 7-21).\r\n\r\nThießen, Malte (2