47	Vienna as a gateway city for the countryside – reconstructing the image of a capital by using digital tools on Oral Histories	Narrative layer: After 1918, as the capital of “Kleinösterreich”, Vienna literally moved closer to the rural population and initiated a process of appropriation. The former imperial city lost its global importance that it gained during the fin-de-siècle. Vienna with almost two million inhabitants was no longer the Imperial city it once was, now surrounded by a few rural federal states in which only 4.5 million people lived. The historian Wolfgang Maderthaner calls this historical break a “demotion” of the city, which had an impact on the perception of Vienna within the Austrian countryside. Furthermore, regular contact between the capital city and the rural areas was based on the installed requisition system – Vienna took food and other resources from the countryside to its own survival. My research questions therefore are: What was the rural population imagine and how did they evaluate Vienna after 1918? How was Vienna perceived, and for what reasons was it visited over the course of the 20th and 21st centuries? Based on 560 transcripts of Oral History interviews, the image of Vienna within the rural parts of Austria was reconstructed. With this type of source, the research project needed new tools and methods for the analysis, especially digital tools for handling the big number of transcripts provided as Microsoft Word files by the audio/visual archive "Österreichische Mediathek". Additionally, the project opens up a new approach by implementing theories from the communication studies and its sub-discipline image research into historiographical analysis. Image has been defined as a “platform of social exchange” through which attributions are negotiated and “appropriated” according to the communication scientist and historian Rainer Gries. Hence, the rural population respectively the interview transcripts were analyzed in their interaction with Vienna and its image. Also, the methodical approach was experimental in the way that sources of qualitative research, which are individual biographies, were processed as data and analyzed with digital tools.\r\nThe findings are structured in a threefold manner: (1) how the interviewees living in the federal states Steiermark, Tirol, Salzburg, and Vorarlberg acquired knowledge about Vienna; (2) what impression Vienna had or has on them – because of self-acquired or transmitted experiences; (3) what meaning and impact did or does Vienna have for them. The subject matter of more than two thirds of the interview transcripts was Vienna. From these cases, more than two thirds of the oral histories, included personal experiences in or about Vienna. Based on my analysis, I argue that the ties between the Austrian capital and the Austrian federal states are strong and important for people living in the rural areas because it shapes them in different ways, such as education, marriage, working possibilities, but also entertainment. In short, the results show that the new image of Vienna, after its Imperial status, was one of a “gateway city” (Musil) to the rural population. Vienna was/is perceived as a city not to stay, but important to cross.\r\n \r\nHermeneutic layer: The findings driven from the Oral history interview transcripts are the outcome of a combination of “traditional” and digital methods. For the digital part, I used the software R in combination with the package “Quanteda”, a tool for “the quantitative analysis of textual data” (Benoit, https://quanteda.io/reference/quanteda-package.html).\r\nBased on the results that I gained with R, a content analysis according to Werner Früh followed, in which I coded the main text corpus gained with R. However, the first steps of analysis could only be done with the aid of digital tools.\r\nThe methodological steps I followed were (1) to create text corpus with inhomogeneous transcripts that I was provided with by the Österreichische Mediathek. Then, I needed to identify and extract the paragraphs, in which Vienna was talked about (keyword-in-context-analysis). (2) Based on this dataset, I created a document consisting of the story teller’s name, their date of birth, where they lived, their gender, and the text snippets containing Vienna. This document served as main corpus for the analytic steps with the package Quanteda, as well as for a classical content analysis according to Werner Früh, who introduced an “interaction analysis” with quantifiable elements. (3) The further usage of digital tools included a frequency analysis (including visualization), a colocation analysis, and the analysis of related words of keyword. (4) Lastly, I combined the results drawn from the digital tools and the content analysis to answer my research questions.\r\n \r\nData layer: The Oral history interview transcripts that created my main corpus are archived in the Österreichische Mediathek and are part of the project, “MenschenLeben” (https://www.mediathek.at/menschenleben/projekt-menschenleben/). A big number of the transcripts from my corpus are available online, but not all of them. To provide online access to all the data is an ongoing process within the Mediathek, and takes time due to the editing of the transcripts by members of the Mediathek. The project "MenschenLeben" exists since 2009 and collects biographical stories through Oral History methods. People who have a connection to Austria, mainly Austrian citizens, are interviewed and asked to speak about their life. Hence, this material describes the individual and collective life experiences of people of all social groups and generations, spanning a whole century. The interviews are recorded and last between 2 to 14 hours (at least, this was the longest interview I personally encountered).\r\nWith the help of Österreichische Mediathek employees, a corpus of 560 interviews was compiled that met the criteria of the project from the more than 1,750 interviews archived in the Mediathek. The selection of the interview transcripts was in accordance with the employees because the data with online access is incomplete. Although the data (transcripts) is digital-born, the (different) methods of archiving it and protecting personal rights made it impossible to get access to all of it. Together with the Österreichische Mediathek employees, I chose to include transcripts from people living in Styria. The majority of interviews archived in the Österreichische Mediathek, were made in this federal state (n = 381). In order to be able to compare results from different rural areas in Austria, I got additionally all interview transcripts from people living in Salzburg, Tirol, and Vorarlberg (n = 179). This second data compilation was created as a “Western” counterpart to the Styrian Oral Histories.\r\nThe interview transcripts, which were transmitted as Word files, showed a broad range of transcribing methods. As such, they were inhomogeneous in style, design, wording and length. One of the first questions I dealt with was how to deal with this source: is it legitimate to compare the transcripts, although they are so different? Which sort of research question can I answer with them the way I want to use this source (namely, quantitative)? Is it possible to bridge results of quantitative and digital analysis with single biographies? How general must the results drawn from Oral Histories be in order to be considered conclusive? The idea of how to methodologically approach this sort of source, I got from the paper written by the historians Cameron Lynne Macdonald and Karen V. Hansen who did a quantitative analysis on various dairies. The new understanding of a digital source criticism I relied on papers published in the book “, especially the one written by Christopher Banditt who defined ways of how to examine internal and external.\r\n \r\nBanditt, Ch. (2022). Die Rekonstruktion der materiellen Ausstattung von Haush