41	The Text Analysis Prototype for GaLiLeO: Galileo's Library and Letters Online	This article reports on a prototype digital laboratory for text analysis and discovery of historical materials related to Galileo Galilei (1563-1642). The full project, GaLiLeO: Galileo's Library and Letters Online, was a collaboration between the author, a digital humanist and Italian literary scholar working in R on the primary sources, and Professor Hannah Marcus, a historian of science working in Python with an editorial apparatus created by a team of specialists. Presented here is an analytical reflection on the text analysis toolkit developed by the author that could potentially be applicable to other collections of historical documents. The critical narrative demonstrates how the tools are complementary to, but not a replacement for, digital interfaces that replicate analog finding and organizational structures for historic documents.\r\n\tThe hermeneutic layer mirrors the Jupyter notebook that was shared at a September 2018 workshop with international specialists in digital humanities, history of science, and Italian Studies. These tools for exploration, question making, and question answering are inspired by a common epistemological practice in Galileo's lifetime: the juxtaposition of objects in a wunderkammer (cabinet of curiosities). In this scenario new knowledge arises from seeing a document in comparison to others, not solely from the inherited value attached to an author, date, or term. Embedded functions allow a user to contextualize a document within a broader corpus of personal and semi-public letters, prefatory letters, and book-length texts from Galileo's library. By providing these contextual details, the digital space becomes experiential and representational, experimental and demonstrative.\r\n\tGaLiLeO prioritizes relationships not typically captured in database design for archival material. The heterogenous document set is not limited by physical institutional collections. While the underlying data can be accessed by searching typical metadata fields, other query options prioritize quantitative and lexical perspectives on the texts. For example, stored data for each word type includes, but is not limited to, frequency in the corpus as well as only in works by Galileo (or not by him), the first and last appearance in the corpus, and if the term is found in a preliminary topic model of the texts. This underlying structure makes it possible to combine more of the hermeneutic strengths of Voyant Tools with a rigorous metadata interface like the ARTFL Encyclopédie. Unlike the latter, a user need not know a search term of interest to generate results.\r\n\tQueries can instead be based on a definition of what is interesting rather than pre-determined names or dates of interest. Historians and literary scholars know the kinds of patterns that reveal fruitful pathways through a collection of documents: marginal or central figures, unusual or highly common terms, and (in)stability of collocates over time. Often, finding a pattern relies on inherited structures of information organization, which can replicate or reinforce systemic biases and invisibility. Accordingly, the preliminary text analysis tools in GaLiLeO represent a prototype to deprioritize post-hoc organizational structures in order to emphasize relationships across documents that may have resisted or otherwise been excluded from such structures.	2022-10-20 10:47:33+00	\N	https://orcid.org/0000-0003-1324-0364	Bowdoin College	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	Hall	Crystal	SUBMITTED	t		FYjDViXVXggz	\N
