nd current limits on more complex forms of historical interpretation.\r\n\r\n1. What Do AIs Know About History?: As LLMs have advanced, so too have their\r\nperformance on a machine learning benchmark familiar to many historians: Advanced Placement History Exams. LLMs have recently surpassed expert-level performance on this benchmark.5\r\n\r\n2. Primary Source Analysis: GPT-3 demonstrates a capacity for historical analysis through the interpretation of primary sources. The model can offer contextualization, determine intent, gauge potential audiences, and consider historiographical interpretation.\r\n\r\n3. Simulating Historical Worldviews: This final section features a generative AI chatbot trained to respond from the perspective of a historical text and its author. The article concludes with an assessment of the model's pedagogical potential and its potential for misuse.6\r\n\r\nI document methods for guiding LLMs to assist in historical research in the article's hermeneutical layer. Structured textual prompts are crucial to unlocking GPT-3's remarkable versatility. The code examples demonstrate how "prompt engineering" techniques can effectively guide GPT-3's generations. Such techniques include Few-shot learning, chain-of-thought\r\nreasoning, and prompt chaining.\r\n\r\n1. Rishi Bommasani, et. al., “On the Opportunities and Risks of Foundation Models.” arXiv 2108.07258v2 (August 2021), https://arxiv.org/pdf/2108.07258.pd\r\n\r\n2. The prompt used for this case study can be found at: https://bit.ly/ocr_prompt (requires OpenAI account).\r\n\r\n3.  Github repo: https://github.com/openai/whisper\r\n\r\n4. OpenAI documentation for text embeddings: https://beta.openai.com/docs/guides/embeddings\r\n\r\n5.  Daniel Hutchinson, “Replication Study: GPT-3's Performance on Historical Fields in the MMLU Benchmarks (May 2022). https://github.com/Dr-Hutchinson/gpt-3_history_benchmark_results.\r\n\r\n6. Examples of these can be found at: Daniel Hutchinson, “What Do AIs Know Abo