67	Unlinked: Conflict Resolution and Structural Balance in the Early Modern Republic of Letters	Narrative layer:\r\nIt is well known that the Republic of Letters – the early modern network of scholarly and scientific community – was a virtual space of friendship and cooperation as well as of enmity. Both aspects have been given ample attention in the qualitative historiography. But in the network analyses which are currently undertaken, the negative ties are left out of the equation. In fact, network studies into the Republic of Letters typically only have looked at surviving correspondence, represented as an unsigned network consisting of positive, collaborative edges. The systematic neglect of conflict that these network representations induce capture only part of the reality of the Republic of Letters and might have led to confounding results on its topological structure. In fact, the consequences of negative ties are often considerably greater than positive interactions; they could result in the breakdown of a network, and hence have a decisive impact on the development of knowledge and the spread of innovation. In this respect, the digital lags behind more traditional approaches of close reading, with historians acknowledging the significance of polemics already from the 1970s onwards.  \r\n\r\nThis article challenges the continuing representation of relations between scholars in purely positive terms. The question then rises how can we integrate hostile relations in a formal network analysis of the Republic of Letters? As a case study, we use the correspondence metadata of the prolific letter writer and librarian Antonio Magliabechi (1633-1714) to examine the role of negative ties on the formation of his network. \r\n\r\nIn accordance with the structural balance theory, we show how Magliabechi approached conflict resolution, highlighting that he intervened in third-party relations to avert imbalance in the learned network. The theory of structural balance – which can be summed up in the ancient proverb “you cannot be friends with your friend’s enemy” – assumes that certain combinations of positive (friendship) and negative (hostility) triads confer stability to the network, while others cause instability. As a result, unstable networks are likely to demand higher levels of conflict management because people are incentivized to increase balance by correcting troublesome relationships, even if this means that they need to rewire their entire network to avoid contact with their enemies. Unstable networks caused by negative ties – in spite of their relative rarity – are thus more likely to drive network change, as compared to a network having only positive ties.\r\n\r\nThe structural balance theory has been used in different areas in the social sciences, to understand, for example, why nations fight wars or how user communities behave on the internet. By contrast, the structural balance theory represents a methodological contribution almost entirely without precedent in the field of history. This article shows a distant reading approach to model the structural changes in the network caused by balanced (+++, +--) and unbalanced triads (---, ++-) and its impact on the developments of the topological structure of the network along with discussions of them. An added value of this article is to explicitly show how decisions are taken in relation to the data, and what their implications are for the interpretation of the findings.\r\n\r\nData layer:\r\nHow did Magliabechi regulate the mix of friendly and hostile relationships in his network? To answer this question, this study takes the correspondence metadata of Magliabechi and uses the Catalogus Epistularum Neerlandicarum (CEN) to contextualize his ego-network. Basic metadata on Magliabechi’s correspondence are captured in a printed inventory. This inventory of 20.575 letters is based on the collections of the National Library of Florence and records the names of Magliabechi’s correspondents as well as the dates and places of sending. The inventory has been OCR’ed and updated using secondary and archival sources. \r\n\r\nThe CEN is a Dutch national union catalogue and consists of approx. 584.723 metadata of single letters and accumulated bilateral epistolary exchanges from 1303 to ca. 2013, held at several Dutch institutions, among which are the Royal Dutch Library and several university libraries. The combination of these two datasets resulted in a second-degree network consisting of more than 25.000 letters exchanged between more than 3000 correspondents. The original data and the resulting combined datasets are made available in a Dataverse repository. All the data preparation steps are shared in a Jupyter notebook: script_dataPreparation_Python_unlinkedArticle_20220512.ipynb which can be found in the Github repository: https://github.com/inge1211/unlinked_historical_structural_balance.\r\n\r\nOn top of this network, layers of data will be placed to enrich the ties with negative signs. However, datasets that store information on hostile edges are noticeably absent in the field of early modern history, likely because of the difficulty of collecting empirical data to examine the nature of relationships. Reconstructing the signed network – a network with both positive and negative ties – for this study thus required a combination of computational analysis and archival work. The annotation of negative ties is collected through a close reading of Magliabechi’s letters extent in library collections of the Netherlands, Germany and Italy. \r\n\r\nSubsequently, the R package Signnet was used to create four configurations of balance and imbalance from a signed network. The entire dataset was sliced per year and these configurations were created for each year within the time range of Magliabechi's active life as correspondent with the Dutch Republic. For each year, thus, four values were obtained, which are displayed in our notebook script_dataAnalysis_R_unlinkedArticle_20220512.ipynb, also available in the repository mentioned above.\r\n\r\nHermeneutical layer:\r\n\r\nReplication in historical research:\r\nUsing digital tools and data brings important challenges to historical research. One of the most important ones in our case is the "messiness" of the letters metadata. One of our main raw sources, the CEN dataset was obtained as a dump in XML format from the Online Computer Library Center (OCLC) and the Royal Dutch Library in October 2019. Preparing the dataset for analysis required a significant amount of effort due to inconsistencies in the original data. Considerably, the dataset underwent an extensive harmonization effort to cluster person name variants (e.g. to eradicate spelling variations of person names, or to detect and merge the different forms in which cataloguers labelled the same person). Similarly, letter year fields were also carefully cleaned. The data processing methods are fully explained in interactive Jupyter notebooks available in this article’s repository.  These notebooks provide step-by-step instructions to replicate this research – starting from the data processing up to the final analysis – offering complete transparency about the decision and assumption making process, as well as the analysis and interpretation. \r\n\r\nDealing with uncertainty:\r\nAnother important challenge of using digital historical data is "incompleteness" and "uncertainty". Indeed, in our case, several letters lacked a year in which they were written. Because for our research we needed to create time intervals in which two persons exchanged letters, we wanted to analyze what the impact in the network analysis would be of using complete vs. incomplete datasets. We approached this challenge by identifying which part of our dataset included complete and certain years vs. the slice of the dataset that didn't have a year or in which this was uncertain. Thus, to avoid introducing noise in the creation of time intervals, we filtered out those correspondent pairs (236 in total) in the CEN or Magliabechi’s inventory where the year of the exchange was missing or contained some degree of uncertainty. In another file, we kept all pairs and assigned a letter date based on the years of birth and death of the correspondents. The results were compared, and we found out that the removal of those 236 pairs had little effect on the resulting counts of (+ – –), (– – –) and (+ + –) triads.  We therefore only included correspondence with dates that were certain in our final analysis (4.386 pairs).    \r\n\r\nWhat is a negative tie?:\r\nAnother challenge in using digital data for historical research is "data absence". The analysis of negative ties required the creation of manual annotations of a given relationship as described above. But this annotation gave rise to important methodological questions: In many ways structural balance can be considered as too simplistic and hence unsuitable to deal with the complexity of past and human interactions. Relationships between people are not easy to categorize in terms of positive and negative edges alone. Early modern scholars were masters of the art of dissimulation and had no difficulties in maintaining a friendly correspondence with persons they distrusted. The picture, therefore, is more nuanced than suggested by the structural balance theory. However, for finding patterns within a large pool of data simplicity is key. Too many assumptions and gradations in the process of data collection will lead to bias and data fragmentation, making the outcomes statistically irrelevant. Based on these questions and reflections, this study clearly underlines that the outcomes of the large-scale analysis are not an end in itself but need to be supported by close reading and historical interpretation.	2022-09-02 11:26:52+00	\N	https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7703-1791	Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences (KNAW)	elisabeth.guerard@uni.lu	van Vugt	Ingeborg