63	https://github.com/jdh-observer/boXXEPfnFTRe	JTJGcHJveHktZ2l0aHVidXNlcmNvbnRlbnQlMkZqZGgtb2JzZXJ2ZXIlMkZib1hYRVBmbkZUUmUlMkZtYWluJTJGYW5vbnltaXplZF9nYW1pbmdfdGhlX3FpbmdfbWFuZGFyaW5hdGVfYV9uZXR3b3JrX2FuZF9tb250ZV9jYXJsb19hcHByb2FjaF90b19hX25pbmV0ZWVudGgtY2VudHVyeV9jaGluZXNlX2JvYXJkZ2FtZS5pcHluYg==		PEER_REVIEW	GITHUB	12	{"title": ["# Gaming the Qing Mandarinate: A Network and Monte Carlo Approach to a Nineteenth-Century Chinese Boardgame"], "abstract": ["How did prospective officials during the late Qing dynasty (1644-1911) learn about and perceive their career options? Our study explores the historical boardgame Mandarin Promotions (Shengguantu 陞官圖). As a career race played with dice, the game resembles Milton Bradley's famous nineteenth-century Checkered Game of Life. However, as it closely mirrors the actual Qing personnel system, Mandarin Promotions is much more complex. We study a late nineteenth-century version reproduced with playable instructions by Puk Wing Kin in 2010, where players hasten from 22 starting positions through 412 positions in 66 departments to reach 18 ranked final positions. We have combined a network approach using a Neo4J graph database and a Monte Carlo simulation approach developed in Python in order to answer three questions: How meritocratic was the imagined official career for the various starting positions which could be broadly categorized into hereditary privilege (including Manchu heritage), the famed imperial examinations, military merit and patronage, and what we call “incipient professionalism”? Secondly, which were the most pivotal positions for a career to the top echelons of the bureaucracy? Finally, given that office purchase is permitted by the game rules (as in the actual Qing bureaucracy) and that it is the only aspect of the game that requires strategy, we ask if purchasing a higher-ranked position early in the game would be a beneficial strategy. Both methods, but especially the simulation of monetary gains in 100,000 playthroughs, revealed the hidden biases of the Qing's monarchic system which defy common perceptions about a rational meritocratic bureaucracy. Hereditary privilege won big, examination enjoyed modest gains, all other paths lost. Modelling the career system as a network showed the centrality of particular positions, especially that of prefect. Comparison with both statutory regulations and studies of the Chinese Government Employee-Qing database provided two insights: First, the gameboard follows pre-1843 regulations, which confirmed its original creation in 1840, the year on the only surviving board that has a date. Secondly, we interpreted the preeminence of the prefect as an expression of the aspirations of examination graduates. Finally, our simulation of various purchase strategies showed that in most circumstances purchase did not reward the player if monetary gain is considered. In conclusion, our playful engagement with the Qing mandarinate did yield new insights into how contemporaries navigated the world of career-making in a diverse yet monarchic society."], "keywords": ["Qing dynasty (1644-1911), Bureaucracy, Boardgame, Graph Database, Monte Carlo"], "contributor": ["### First Author\\n \\n", "### Second Author\\n \\n"]}	https://mybinder.org/v2/gh/jdh-observer/boXXEPfnFTRe/main?filepath=anonymized_gaming_the_qing_mandarinate_a_network_and_monte_carlo_approach_to_a_nineteenth-century_chinese_boardgame.ipynb.ipynb	anonymized_gaming_the_qing_mandarinate_a_network_and_monte_carlo_approach_to_a_nineteenth-century_chinese_boardgame.ipynb	{}	{"cells": [{"tags": ["title"], "type": "markdown", "isTable": false, "isFigure": false, "countRefs": 0, "isHeading": true, "countChars": 107, "firstWords": "Gaming the Qing Mandarinate: A Network and Monte Carlo", "isMetadata": true, "isHermeneutic": false}, {"tags": ["contributor"], "type": "markdown", "isTable": false, "isFigure": false, "countRefs": 0, "isHeading": true, "countChars": 18, "firstWords": "First Author"